\id JER - Brenton English Septuagint 
\h Jeremiah 
\toc1 Jeremiah 
\toc2 Jeremiah 
\toc3 Jer. 
\mt1 JEREMIAS 
\c 1 
\p
\v 1 \sc The\sc* word of God which came to Jeremiah the \add son\add* of Chelcias, one of the priests, \f + \fr 1:1 \ft The `who' refers to Jeremiah, not the priests. This is unambiguous in the Greek.\f*who dwelt in Anathoth in the land of Benjamin: 
\v 2 \add accordingly\add* as the word of God came to him in the days of Josiah son of Amos king of Judah, in the thirteenth year of his reign. 
\v 3 It was in the days of Joakim son of Josiah king of Judah, until the eleventh year of Zedekiah king of Judah, \add even\add* until the captivity of Jerusalem in the fifth month. 
\p
\v 4 The word of the Lord came to him, \add saying\add*, 
\v 5 Before I formed you in the belly, I knew you; and before you came forth from the womb, I sanctified you; I appointed you a prophet to the nations. 
\p
\v 6 I said, O Lord, you who are supreme Lord, behold, I don't know \add how\add* to speak, for I am a child. 
\v 7 The Lord said to me, Don't say, I am a child: for you will go to all to whoever I will send you, and according to all \add the words\add* that I will command you, you will speak. 
\v 8 Don't be afraid before them: for I am with you to deliver you, says the Lord. 
\v 9 The Lord stretched forth his hand to me, and touched my mouth: and the Lord said to me, Behold, I have put my words into your mouth. 
\p
\v 10 Behold, I have appointed you this day over nations and over kingdoms, to root out, and to pull down, and to destroy, and to rebuild, and to plant. 
\p
\v 11 The word of the Lord came to me, saying, What do you see? And I said, A rod of an almond tree. 
\v 12 The Lord said to me, You have seen well: for I have watched over my words to perform them. 
\v 13 The word of the Lord came to me a second time, saying, What do you see? And I said, A caldron on the fire; and the face of it is toward the north. 
\v 14 The Lord said to me, From the north will flame forth evils upon all the inhabitants of the land. 
\v 15 For, behold, I call together all the kingdoms of the earth from the north, says the Lord; and they will come, and each one will set his throne at the entrance of the gates of Jerusalem, and against all the walls round about her, and against all the cities of Judah. 
\v 16 I will speak to them in judgment, concerning all their wickedness, \add forasmuch\add* as they have forsaken me, and sacrificed to foreign gods, and worshipped the works of their own hands. 
\p
\v 17 Gird up your loins, and stand up, and speak all \add the words\add* that I will command you: don't be afraid of their face, neither be alarmed before them; for I am with you to deliver you, says the Lord. 
\v 18 Behold, I have made you this day as a strong city, and as a bronze wall, strong \add against\add* all the kings of Judah, and the princes of it, and the people of the land. 
\v 19 They will fight against you; but they will surely not prevail against you; because I am with you, to deliver you, says the Lord. 
\c 2 
\p
\v 2 He said, Thus says the Lord, I remember the kindness of your youth, and the love of your espousals, in following the Holy One of Israel, says the Lord. 
\v 3 Israel was the holy \add people\add* to the Lord, \add and\add* the first-fruits of his increase: all who devoured him will offend; evils will come upon them, says the Lord. 
\p
\v 4 Hear the word of the Lord, O house of Jacob, and every family of the house of Israel. 
\v 5 Thus says the Lord, What trespass have your fathers found in me, that they have revolted far from me, and gone after vanities, and become vain? 
\v 6 They didn't say, Where is the Lord, who brought us up out of the land of Egypt, who guided us in the wilderness, in an untried and trackless land, in a land which no man at all went through, and no man dwelt there? 
\v 7 I brought you to Carmel, that you should eat the fruits of it, and the good of it; and you went in, and defiled my land, and made my heritage an abomination. 
\v 8 The priests didn't say, Where is the Lord? And those who held by the law didn't know me: the shepherds also sinned against me, and the prophets prophesied by Baal, and went after that which didn't profit. 
\p
\v 9 Therefore I will yet plead with you, and will plead with your children's children. 
\v 10 For go to the isles of the Chettians, and see; and send to Kedar, and observe accurately, and see if such things have been done; 
\v 11 if the nations will change their gods, though they are not gods: but my people have changed their glory, \add for that\add* from which they will not be profited. 
\v 12 The heaven is amazed at this, and is very exceedingly horror-struck, says the Lord. 
\v 13 For my people has committed two \add faults\add*, and evil ones: they have forsaken me, the fountain of water of life, and hewn out for themselves broken cisterns, which will not be able to hold water. 
\p
\v 14 Is Israel a servant, or a home-born slave? Why has he become a spoil? 
\v 15 The lions roared upon him, and uttered their voice, which have made his land a wilderness: and his cities are broken down, that they should not be inhabited. 
\v 16 Also the children of Memphis and Taphnas have known you, and mocked you. 
\v 17 Has not your forsaking me brought these things upon you? Says the Lord your God. 
\p
\v 18 Now what do you have to do with the way of Egypt, to drink the water of Geon? And what do you have to do with the way of the Assyrians, to drink the water of rivers? 
\v 19 Your apostasy will correct you, and your wickedness will reprove you: know then, and see, that your forsaking me \add has been\add* bitter to you, says the Lord your God; and I have taken no pleasure in you, says the Lord your God. 
\p
\v 20 For of old you have broken your yoke, and plucked apart your bands; and you have said, I will not serve you, but will go on every high hill, and under every shady tree, there will I indulge in my prostitution. 
\v 21 Yet I planted you a fruitful vine, entirely of the right sort: how are you a foreign vine turned to bitterness! 
\v 22 Though \f+ \fr 2:22 \fqa Gr. \ft he/she\f*you wash with soap, and you use plenty of lye, \add still\add* you are stained by your iniquities before me, says the Lord. 
\p
\v 23 How will you say, I am not polluted, and have not gone after Baal? Behold your ways in the burial-ground, and know what you have done: her voice has howled in the evening: 
\v 24 she has extended her ways over the waters of the desert; she was hurried along by the lusts of her soul; she is given up \add to them\add*, who will turn her back? None who seek her will be weary; at \add the time of\add* her humiliation they will find her. 
\v 25 Withdraw your foot from a rough way, and your throat from thirst: but she said, I will strengthen myself: for she loved strangers, and went after them. 
\p
\v 26 As is the shame of a thief when he is caught, so will the children of Israel be ashamed; they, and their kings, and their princes, and their priests, and their prophets. 
\v 27 They said to the wood, You are my father; and to a stone, You have begotten me: and they have turned \add their\add* backs to me, and not their faces: yet in the time of their afflictions they will say, Arise, and save us. 
\v 28 Where are your gods, which you made for yourself? Will they arise and save in the time of your affliction? For according to the number of your cities were your gods, O Judah; and according to the number of the streets of Jerusalem they sacrificed to Baal. 
\v 29 Why do you speak to me? You all have been ungodly, and you all have transgressed against me, says the Lord. 
\v 30 In vain have I struck your children; you have not received correction: a sword has devoured your prophets as a destroying lion; yet you didn't fear. 
\p
\v 31 Hear the word of the Lord: thus says the Lord, Have I been a wilderness or a dry land to Israel? Why has my people said, We will not be ruled over, and will not come to you any more? 
\v 32 Will a bride forget her ornaments, or a virgin her girdle? But my people has forgotten me days without number. 
\v 33 What fair device will you yet employ in your ways, so as to seek love? \add it will\add* not \add be\add* so; moreover you have done wickedly in corrupting your ways; 
\v 34 and in your hands has been found the blood of innocent souls; I have not found them in holes, but on every oak. 
\v 35 Yet you said, I am innocent: only let his wrath be turned away from me. 
\p Behold, I contend with you, because you say, I have not sinned. 
\v 36 For you have been so exceedingly contemptuous as to repeat your ways; but you will be ashamed of Egypt, as you were ashamed of Assur. 
\v 37 For you will go forth from there also with your hands upon your head; for the Lord has rejected your hope, and you will not prosper in it. 
\c 3 
\p
\v 1 If a man puts away his wife, and she departs from him, and becomes another man's, will she return to him again? Won't that woman be completely defiled? Yet you have prostituted yourself with many shepherds, and will you return to me? says the Lord. 
\v 2 Lift up your eyes \add to look\add* straight ahead, and see: where haven't you been defiled? You sat for them by the wayside like a crow in the wilderness, and you defiled the land with your fornications and your wickedness. 
\v 3 You retained many shepherds for a stumbling-block to yourself: you had a prostitute's face, you became shameless toward all. 
\p
\v 4 Haven't you called me your home, and father, and guide of your youth? 
\v 5 Will \add God's anger\add* continue forever, or be preserved to the end? Behold, you have spoken and done these bad things, and had power \add to do them\add*. 
\p
\v 6 The Lord said to me in the days of Josiah the king, Have you seen what things the house of Israel has done to me? They have gone on every high mountain, and under every shady tree, and have committed prostitution there. 
\v 7 I said after she had committed all these acts of prostitution, Turn again to me. Yet she didn't return. And faithless Judah saw her faithlessness. 
\v 8 I saw that (for all the sins of which she was convicted, wherein the house of Israel committed adultery, and I put her away, and gave into her hands a bill of divorcement,) yet faithless Judah didn't fear, but went and herself also committed prostitution. 
\v 9 Her prostitution counted for nothing; and she committed adultery with wood and stone. 
\v 10 For all these things faithless Judah didn't turn to me with all her heart, but falsely. 
\p
\v 11 The Lord said to me, Israel has justified himself more than faithless Judah. 
\v 12 Go and read these words toward the north, and you will say, Return to me, O house of Israel, says the Lord; and I will not set my face against you: for I am merciful, says the Lord, and I will not be angry with you forever. 
\v 13 Nevertheless, know your wickedness, that you have sinned against the Lord your God, and have scattered your ways to strangers under every shady tree, but you did not listen to my voice, says the Lord. 
\v 14 Turn, you children who have revolted, says the Lord; for I will rule over you: and I will take you one from a city, and two from a family, and I will bring you in to Zion: 
\v 15 and I will give you shepherds after my heart, and they will certainly tend you with knowledge. 
\p
\v 16 It will come to pass that when you are multiplied and increased upon the land, says the Lord, in those days they will say no more, The ark of the covenant of the Holy One of Israel: it will not come to mind; it will not be named; neither will it be visited; nor will \add this\add* be done any more. 
\v 17 In those days and at that time they will call Jerusalem the throne of the Lord; and all the nations will be gathered to it: and they will not walk any more after the imaginations of their evil heart. 
\p
\v 18 In those days the house of Judah will come together to the house of Israel, and they will come, together, from the land of the north, and from all the lands, to the land, which I caused their fathers to inherit. 
\v 19 I said, So be it, Lord, for \add you said\add*, I will set you among children, and will give you a choice land, the inheritance of the Almighty God of the nations: and I said, You will call me Father; and you will not turn away from me. 
\v 20 But as a wife acts treacherously against her husband, so has the house of Israel dealt treacherously against me, says the Lord. 
\p
\v 21 A voice from the lips was heard, \add even\add* of weeping and supplication of the children of Israel: for they have dealt unrighteously in their ways, they have forgotten God their Holy One. 
\v 22 Turn, you children who are given to turning, and I will heal your bruises. 
\p Behold, we will be your servants; for you are the Lord our God. 
\v 23 Truly the hills and the strength of the mountains proved to be a lie: but the salvation of Israel is through the Lord our God.
\v 24 But shame has consumed the labours of our fathers from our youth; their sheep and their calves, and their sons and their daughters. 
\v 25 We have lain down in our shame, and our disgrace has covered us: because we and our fathers have sinned before our God, from our youth until this day; and we have not listened to the voice of the Lord our God. 
\c 4 
\p
\v 1 If Israel returns, says the Lord, he will return to me: and if he will remove his abominations out of his mouth, and show reverence before me,
\v 2 and if he swears, As the Lord lives, with truth, in justice and righteousness, then will nations bless themselves by him, and by him they will praise God in Jerusalem. 
\p
\v 3 For thus says the Lord to the men of Judah, and to the inhabitants of Jerusalem, Break up fresh ground for yourselves, and don't sow among thorns. 
\v 4 Circumcise yourselves to your God, and circumcise your hardness of heart, you men of Judah, and inhabitants of Jerusalem: lest my wrath go forth as fire, and burn, and there be none to quench it, because of the evil of your devices. 
\p
\v 5 Declare in Judah, and let it be heard in Jerusalem: say, Sound the trumpet in the land; cry aloud: say, Gather yourselves together, and let us enter into the fortified cities. 
\v 6 Gather up \add your wares\add* and flee to Zion: hasten, don't stay: for I will bring evils from the north, and great destruction. 
\v 7 The lion has gone up from his lair, he has roused \add himself\add* to the destruction of the nations, and has gone forth out of his place, to make the land desolate; and the cities will be destroyed, so as to be without inhabitant. 
\v 8 For these things gird yourselves with sackclothes, and lament, and howl: for the anger of the Lord hasn't turned away from you. 
\v 9 It will come to pass in that day, says the Lord, that the heart of the king will perish, and the heart of the princes; and the priests will be amazed, and the prophets will wonder. 
\p
\v 10 I said, O sovereign Lord, truly you have greatly deceived this people and Jerusalem, saying, There will be peace; because behold, the sword has reached even to their soul. 
\p
\v 11 At that time they will say to this people and to Jerusalem, \add There is\add* a spirit of error in the wilderness: the way of the daughter of my people isn't to purity, nor to holiness. 
\v 12 \add But\add* a spirit of full vengeance will come upon me; and now I declare my judgments against them. 
\v 13 Behold, he will come up as a cloud, and his chariots as a tempest: his horses are swifter than eagles. Woe to us! For we are in misery. 
\p
\v 14 Cleanse your heart from wickedness, O Jerusalem, that you may be saved: how long will your grievous thoughts be within you? 
\v 15 For a voice of one proclaiming from Dan will come, and trouble out of mount Ephraim will be heard of. 
\v 16 Remind the nations; behold, they have come: proclaim \add it\add* in Jerusalem, that bands are approaching from a land far off, and have uttered their voice against the cities of Judah. 
\v 17 As keepers of a field, they have surrounded her; because you, says the Lord, have neglected me. 
\v 18 Your ways and your devices have brought these things upon you; this is your wickedness, because \add it is\add* bitter, because it has reached to your heart. 
\p
\v 19 My belly, my belly: I am in pain! And the feelings of my heart! My soul is in great commotion, my heart is torn: I will not be silent, for my soul has heard the sound of a trumpet, the cry of war, and of distress: it calls on destruction; 
\v 20 for all the land has been devestated: suddenly \add my\add* tent is destroyed, my tend-curtains have been torn apart. 
\v 21 How long will I see fugitives, and hear the sound of the trumpet? 
\p
\v 22 For the princes of my people have not known me, they are foolish and unwise children: they are wise to do evil, but they have not know \add how\add* to do good.
\p
\v 23 I looked on the earth, and, behold, nothing; and to the sky, and there was no light. 
\v 24 I beheld the mountains, and they trembled, and \add I saw\add* all the hills were shaking.
\v 25 I looked, and, behold, there was no man, and all the birds of the sky had fled. 
\v 26 I saw, and, behold, Carmel was desert, and all the cities were burnt with fire at the presence of the Lord, and at the presence of his fierce anger they were completely destroyed. 
\p
\v 27 Thus says the Lord, The whole land will be desolate; but I will surely not make a full end. 
\v 28 For these things let the earth mourn, and let the sky be dark above: for I have spoken, and I will not repent; I have purposed, and I will not turn back from it. 
\v 29 The whole land has recoiled from the noise of the horseman and the bent bow; they have gone into the caves, and have hidden themselves in the groves, and have gone up on the rocks: every city was abandoned, no man dwelt in them. 
\v 30 What will you do? Though you clothe yourself with scarlet, and adorn yourself with golden ornaments; though you adorn your eyes with stibium, your beauty \add will be\add* in vain: your lovers have rejected you, they seek your life. 
\p
\v 31 For I have heard your groaning as the voice of a woman in labor, as of her who brings forth her first child; the voice of the daughter of Zion will fail through weakness, and she will lose the strength of her hands, \add saying\add*, Woe is me! For my soul faints because of the killed. 
\c 5 
\p
\v 1 Run about in the streets of Jerusalem, and see, and know, and seek in her broad places, if you can find \add one\add*, if there is any one who does justice, and seeks faithfulness; and I will pardon them, says the Lord. 
\v 2 The Lord lives, they say; do they not therefore swear falsely? 
\v 3 O Lord, your eyes are upon faithfulness: you have scourged them, but they have not grieved; you have consumed them; but they would not receive correction: they have made their faces harder than a rock; and they would not return. 
\v 4 Then I said, It may be they are poor; for they are weak, for they don't know the way of the Lord, or the judgment of God. 
\v 5 I will go to the rich men, and will speak to them; for they have known the way of the Lord, and the judgment of God: but, behold, with one consent they have broken the yoke, they have burst the bonds. 
\p
\v 6 Therefore a lion out of the forest has struck them, and a wolf has destroyed them even to \add their\add* houses, and a leopard has watched against their cities: all who go forth from them will be hunted: for they have multiplied their ungodliness, they have strengthened themselves in their revoltings. 
\v 7 For which of these things will I forgive you? Your sons have forsaken me, and sworn by those who are not gods: I fed them to the full, and they committed adultery, and lodged in harlots' houses. 
\v 8 They became as wanton horses: each one neighed after his neighbour's wife. 
\v 9 Will I not visit for these things? Says the Lord: and will my soul not be avenged on such a nation as this. 
\p
\v 10 Go up on her battlements, and break \add them\add* down; but don't make a full end: leave her buttresses; for they are the Lord's. 
\v 11 For the house of Israel have indeed dealt treacherously against me, says the Lord: the house of Judah also 
\v 12 have lied to their Lord, and they have said, These things are not so; no evils will come upon us; and we will not see sword or famine. 
\v 13 Our prophets became wind, and the word of the Lord was not in them. 
\p
\v 14 Therefore thus says the Lord Almighty, Because you have spoken this word, behold, I have made my words in \f + \fr 14 \ft The Greek switches from plural ``you have spoken'' to singular ``your mouth'' signalling a shift of address from the people to the prophet.\f*your mouth fire, \add O prophet,\add* and this people wood, and it will devour them. 
\v 15 Behold, I \add will\add* bring upon you a nation from far, O house of Israel, says the Lord; a nation the sound of whose language one will not understand. 
\v 16 \add They are\add* all mighty men: 
\v 17 and they will devour your harvest, and your bread; and will devour your sons, and your daughters; and they will devour your sheep, and your calves, and devour your vineyards, and your fig-plantations, and your olive yards: and they will completely destroy your strong cities, wherein you trusted, with the sword. 
\v 18 It will come to pass in those days, says the Lord your God, that I will not completely destroy you. 
\p
\v 19 It will come to pass, when you will say, Why has the Lord our God done all these things to us? That you will say to them, Because you served foreign gods in your land, so will you serve strangers in a land that isn't yours. 
\p
\v 20 Proclaim these things to the house of Jacob, and let them be heard in the house of Judah. 
\v 21 Now hear these things, O foolish and senseless people; who have eyes, and don't see; and have ears, and don't hear: 
\v 22 will you not be afraid of me? Says the Lord; and will you not fear before me, who have set the sand for a bound to the sea, \add as\add* a perpetual ordinance, and it will not pass it: yes, it will rage, but not prevail; and its waves will roar, but not pass over it. 
\p
\v 23 But this people has a disobedient and rebellious heart; and they have turned aside and gone back: 
\v 24 and they have not said in their heart, Let us fear now the Lord our God, who gives us the early and late rain, according to the season of the fulfilment of the ordinance of harvest, and has preserved \add it\add* for us. 
\v 25 Your transgressions have turned away these things, and your sins have removed good things from you. 
\v 26 For among my people were found ungodly men; and they have set snares to destroy men, and have caught \add them\add*. 
\p
\v 27 As a snare which has been set is full of birds, so are their houses full of deceit: therefore have they grown great, and become rich: 
\v 28 and they have transgressed \add the rule of\add* judgment; they have not judged the cause of the orphan, nor have they judged the cause of the widow. 
\v 29 Will I not visit for these things? Says the Lord: and won't my soul be avenged on such a nation as this? 
\p
\v 30 Shocking and horrible deeds have been done on the land; 
\v 31 the prophets utter unrighteous prophecies, and the priests have clapped their hands: and my people has loved \add to have it\add* thus: and what will you do for the future? 
\c 6 
\p
\v 1 Strengthen yourselves, you children of Benjamin, \add to flee\add* out of the midst of Jerusalem, and sound an alarm with the trumpet in Thecue, and set up a signal over Bæthacharma: for evil threatens from the north, and a great destruction is coming. 
\v 2 And \add your\add* pride, O daughter of Zion, will be taken away. 
\v 3 The shepherds and their flocks will come to her; and they will pitch \add their\add* tents against her round about, and will feed \add their flocks\add* each with his hand. 
\p
\v 4 Prepare yourselves for war against her; rise up, and let us go up against her at noon. Woe to us! For the day has gone down, for the shadows of the day fail. 
\v 5 Rise, and let us go up against her by night, and destroy her foundations. 
\p
\v 6 For thus says the Lord, Hew down her trees, array a numerous force against Jerusalem. O false city; \add there is\add* all oppression in her. 
\v 7 As a cistern cools water, so her wickedness cools her, ungodliness and misery will be heard in her, \add as\add* continually before her. 
\p
\v 8 You will be chastened, O Jerusalem, with pain and the scourge, lest my soul depart from you; lest I make you a desert land, which will not be inhabited. 
\p
\v 9 For thus says the Lord, Glean, glean thoroughly as a vine the remnant of Israel: turn back \add your hands\add* as a grape-gatherer to his basket. 
\v 10 To whom will I speak, and testify, that he may listen? Behold, your ears are uncircumcised, and they will not be able to hear: behold, the word of the Lord has become to them a reproach, they will surely not desire it. 
\p
\v 11 I allowed my wrath to come to the full, yet I kept \add it\add* in, and did not completely destroy them: I will pour it out on the children outside, and on the assembly of young men together: for man and woman will be taken together, the old man with him who is full of days. 
\v 12 Their houses will be turned to others, \add with\add* their fields and their wives together: for I will stretch out my hand upon the inhabitants of this land, says the Lord. 
\p
\v 13 For from the least of them to the greatest they have all committed wickedness; from the priest to the false prophet they have all worked falsely. 
\v 14 They healed the breach of my people \add imperfectly\add*, making light \add of it\add*, and saying, Peace, peace: and where is peace? 
\v 15 They were ashamed because they failed; yet they were not ashamed as those who are \add truly\add* ashamed, and they didn't know their own disgrace: therefore will they \add completely\add* fall when they do fall, and in the time of visitation they will perish, said the Lord. 
\p
\v 16 Thus says the Lord, Stand in the ways, and see, and ask the Lord for the old paths; and see what is the good way, and walk in it, and you will find purification for your souls. But they said, We will not walk \add in them\add*. 
\v 17 I have set watchmen over you, \add saying\add*, Hear the sound of the trumpet. But they said, We will not hear \add it\add*. 
\p
\v 18 Therefore the nations have heard, and those who feed their flocks. 
\v 19 Hear, O earth: behold, I will bring evils upon this people, \add even\add* the fruit of their rebellions; for they have not heeded my words, and they have rejected my law. 
\v 20 Why do you bring me frankincense from Saba, and cinnamon from a land far off? Your whole-burnt-offerings are not acceptable, and your sacrifices have not been pleasant to me. 
\v 21 Therefore thus says the Lord, Behold, I \add will\add* bring weakness upon this people, and the fathers and sons will be weak together; the neighbour and his friend will perish. 
\p
\v 22 Thus says the Lord, Behold, a people comes from the north, and nations will be stirred up from the end of the earth. 
\v 23 They will lay hold of bow and spear; \add the people\add* is fierce, and will have no mercy; their voice is as the roaring sea; they will array themselves for war against you like fire on horses and chariots, O daughter of Zion. 
\p
\v 24 We have heard the report of them: our hands are weakened: anguish has seized us, the pangs as of a woman in labor. 
\v 25 Don't go forth into the field, and don't walk on the roads; for the sword of the enemy lingers round about. 
\v 26 O daughter of my people, gird yourself with sackcloth: sprinkle \add yourself\add* with ashes; make for yourself pitiable lamentation, \add as\add* the mourning for a beloved \add son\add*: for misery will suddenly come upon you. 
\p
\v 27 I have made you a tester among my people, who have been tested; and you will know me when I test their way. 
\v 28 \add They are\add* all disobedient, walking perversely: \add they are\add* brass and iron; they are all corrupted. 
\v 29 The bellows have failed from the fire, the lead has failed: the silversmith works at his trade in vain; their wickedness isn't consumed. 
\v 30 Call them rejected silver, because the Lord has rejected them. 
\c 7 
\p
\v 2 Hear the word of the Lord, all Judea. 
\v 3 Thus says the Lord God of Israel, Correct your ways and your practices, and I will cause you to dwell in this place. 
\v 4 Don't trust in yourselves with lying words, for they will not profit you at all, saying, The temple of the Lord, it is the temple of the Lord. 
\p
\v 5 For if you thoroughly correct your ways and your practices, and truly execute judgment between a man and his neighbour; 
\v 6 and don't oppress the stranger, and the orphan, and the widow, and don't shed innocent blood in this place, and don't go after foreign gods to your hurt: 
\v 7 then will I cause you to dwell in this place, in the land which I gave to your fathers of old and forever. 
\p
\v 8 But because you have trusted in lying words, by which you will not be profited, 
\v 9 and you murder, and commit adultery, and steal, and swear falsely, and burn incense to Baal, and have gone after foreign gods whom you don't know, 
\v 10 so that it is evil with you; yet have you come, and stood before me in the house, on which my name has been called, and you have said, We have refrained from doing all these abominations. 
\v 11 Is my house, on which my name has been called, a den of robbers in your eyes? And, behold, I have seen \add it\add*, says the Lord. 
\v 12 For go to my place which is in Shiloh, where I caused my name to dwell before, and see what I did to it because of the wickedness of my people Israel. 
\p
\v 13 Now, because you have done all these deeds, and I spoke to you but you didn't listen to me; and I called you but you didn't answer; 
\v 14 therefore I also will do to the house on which my name has been called, in which you trust, and to the place which I gave to you and to your fathers, as I did to Shiloh. 
\v 15 I will cast you out of my sight, as I cast away your brothers, all the seed of Ephraim. 
\p
\v 16 Therefore don't pray for this people, and don't intercede for them to be pitied, yes, don't pray, and don't approach me for them: for I will not listen \add to you\add*. 
\v 17 Don't you see what they do in the cities of Judah, and in the streets of Jerusalem? 
\v 18 Their children gather wood, and their fathers kindle a fire, and their women knead dough, to make cakes to the host of heaven; and they have poured out drink-offerings to foreign gods, that they might provoke me to anger. 
\v 19 Do they provoke me to anger? Says the Lord: don't they \add provoke\add* themselves, that their faces may be ashamed? 
\p
\v 20 Therefore thus says the Lord; Behold, my anger and wrath will be poured out upon this place, and upon the men, and upon the cattle, and upon every tree of their field, and upon the fruits of the land; and it will burn, and not be quenched. 
\p
\v 21 Thus says the Lord, Gather your whole-burnt-offerings with your food-offerings, and eat meat. 
\v 22 For I didn't speak to your fathers, and didn't commanded them in the day in which I brought them up out of the land of Egypt, concerning whole-burnt-offerings and sacrifice: 
\v 23 but I commanded them this thing, saying, Hear my voice, and I will be your God, and you will be my people: and walk in all my ways, which I will command you, that it may be well with you. 
\v 24 But they didn't listen to me, and their ear gave no heed, but they walked in the imaginations of their evil heart, and went backward, and not forward; 
\v 25 from the day that their fathers went out out of the land of Egypt, even until this day. And I sent to you all my servants, the prophets, by day and early in the morning: yes, I sent \add them\add*, 
\v 26 but they didn't listen to me, and their ear gave no heed; and they made their neck harder than their fathers. 
\p
\v 27 Therefore you will speak this word to them: 
\v 28 This is the nation which has not listened to the voice of the Lord, nor received correction: truth has failed from their mouth. 
\p
\v 29 Cut off your hair, and cast it away, and take up a lamentation on your lips; for the Lord has rejected and cast off the generation that does these things. 
\v 30 For the children of Judah have worked evil before me, says the Lord; they have set their abominations in the house on which my name is called, to defile it. 
\v 31 They have built the altar of Tapheth, which is in the valley of the son of Ennom, to burn their sons and their daughters with fire; which I did not command them \add to do\add*, neither did I design it in my heart. 
\p
\v 32 Therefore, behold, days are coming, says the Lord, when they will no more say, The altar of Tapheth, and the valley of the son of Ennom, but, The valley of the killed; and they will bury in Tapheth, for want of room. 
\v 33 The dead bodies of this people will be for food to the birds of the sky, and to the wild beasts of the earth; and there will be none to drive \add them\add* away. 
\v 34 I will destroy out of the cities of Judah, and the streets of Jerusalem, the voice of those who make merry, and the voice of those who rejoice, the voice of the bridegroom, and the voice of the bride; for the whole land will become a desolation. 
\c 8 
\p
\v 1 At that time, says the Lord, they will bring out the bones of the kings of Judah, and the bones of his princes, and the bones of the priests, and the bones of the prophets, and the bones of the inhabitants of Jerusalem, out of their graves; 
\v 2 and they will spread them out to the sun, and the moon, and to all the stars, and to all the host of heaven, which they have loved, and which they have served, and after which they have walked, and to which they have held, and which they have worshipped; they will not be mourned for, neither they will be buried; but they will be for an example on the face of the earth, 
\v 3 because they chose death rather than life, even to all the remnant who are left of that family, in every place where I will drive them out. 
\p
\v 4 For thus says the Lord, Won't the one who falls get up? Or won't the one who turns away turn back again? 
\v 5 Why has this my people turned away with a shameless revolting, and strengthened themselves in their wilfulness, and refused to return? 
\v 6 Listen, please, and hear: they don't speak thus; no one repents of his wickedness, saying, What have I done? Each one has turned aside from his course, like a sweating horse in its neighing. 
\v 7 Yes, the stork in the heaven knows her time, \add also\add* the turtle-dove and wild swallow; the sparrows observe the times of their coming in; but this my people doesn't know the judgments of the Lord. 
\p
\v 8 How will you say, We are wise, and the law of the Lord is with us? In vain have the scribes used a false pen. 
\v 9 The wise men are ashamed, and alarmed, and taken; because they have rejected the word of the Lord; what wisdom is there in them? 
\v 10 Therefore I will give their wives to others, and their fields to \add new\add* inheritors; and they will gather their fruits, says the Lord. 
\v 13 There are no grapes on the vines, and there are no figs on the fig-trees, and the leaves have fallen off. 
\p
\v 14 Why do we sit still? Assemble yourselves, and let us enter into the strong cities, and let us be cast out there: for God has cast us out, and made us drink water of \f + \fr 8:14 \ft Water should sustain life but the image here is of water that is bitter, harmful, even lethal.\f*gall, because we have sinned before him. 
\v 15 We assembled for peace, but there was no prosperity; for a time of healing, but behold anxiety. 
\p
\v 16 We will hear the neighing of his swift horses out of Dan: the whole land quaked at the sound of the neighing of his horses; and he will come, and devour the land and its fulness; the city, and those who dwell in it. 
\v 17 For, behold, I send forth deadly snakes against you, which cannot be charmed, and they will bite you 
\v 18 mortally with the pain of your distressed heart. 
\p
\v 19 Behold, \add there is\add* a sound of the cry of the daughter of my people from a land afar off: Isn't the Lord in Zion? Is there not a king there? Because they have provoked me with their graven \add images\add*, and with foreign vanities. 
\v 20 The summer is gone, the harvest is past, and we are not saved. 
\p
\v 21 For the breach of the daughter of my people I have been saddened: in my perplexity pangs have seized upon me as of a woman in labor. 
\v 22 Is there no balm in Gilead, or is there no physician there? Why hasn't the healing of the daughter of my people taken place? 
\p
\v 23 Who will give water to my head, and a fountain of tears to my eyes? Then would I weep for this my people day and night, \add even\add* for the killed of the daughter of my people. 
\c 9 
\p
\v 1 Who would give me a most distant lodge in the wilderness, that I might leave my people, and depart from them? For they all commit adultery, an assembly of treacherous men. 
\v 2 They have bent their tongue like a bow: falsehood and not faithfulness has prevailed upon the earth; for they have gone on from evil to evil, and have not known me, says the Lord. 
\v 3 Everyone, beware of your neighbour, and don't trust in your brothers: for every brother will surely deal treacherously, and every friend will walk deceitfully. 
\v 4 Every one will mock his friend; they will not speak truth: their tongue has learned to speak lies; they have committed wickedness, they haven't ceased, so as to return. 
\v 5 \add There is\add* usury upon usury, and deceit upon deceit: they were unwilling to know me, says the Lord. 
\p
\v 6 Therefore thus says the Lord, Behold, I will try them with fire, and prove them; for I will do \add thus\add* because of the wickedness of the daughter of my people. 
\v 7 Their tongue is a wounding arrow; the words of their mouth are deceitful: \add one\add* speaks peaceably to his neighbour, but in himself retains enmity. 
\v 8 Will I not visit for these things? Says the Lord: and will not my soul be avenged on such a people as this? 
\v 9 Take up a lamentation for the mountains, and a mournful dirge for the paths of the wilderness, for they are desolate for want of men; they didn't hear the sound of life from the birds of the sky, nor the cattle: they were amazed, they have gone. 
\v 10 I will remove the inhabitants of Jerusalem, and make it a haunt of \ft + \fr 9:10 \fqa Gr. \ft δρακόντων traditionally rendered as 'dragons' (but not referring to mythical creatures).\f*wild creatures; and I will completely waste the cities of Judah, so that they will not be inhabited. 
\p
\v 11 Who is the wise man, that he may understand this? And he who has the word of the mouth of the Lord \add addressed\add* to him, let him tell you why the land has been destroyed, has been ravaged by fire like a desert, so that no one passes through it. 
\v 12 The Lord said to me, Because they have forsaken my law, which I set before them, and have not listened to my voice; 
\v 13 but went after the lusts of their evil heart, and after the idols which their fathers taught them \add to worship\add*: 
\v 14 therefore thus says the Lord God of Israel, Behold, I will feed them with trouble and will cause them to drink water of \f + \fr 9:14 \ft see note to 8:14.\f*gall: 
\v 15 and I will scatter them among the nations, to them whom neither they nor their fathers knew; and I will send a sword upon them, until I have consumed them with it. 
\p
\v 16 Thus says the Lord, Call the mourning women, and let them come; and send to the wise women, and let them utter their voice; 
\v 17 and let them take up a lamentation for you, and let your eyes pour down tears, and your eyelids drop water. 
\v 18 For a voice of lamentation has been heard in Zion, How we have become wretched! We are greatly ashamed, for we have forsaken the land, and have abandoned our tents! 
\v 19 Hear now, you women, the word of God, and let your ears receive the words of his mouth, and teach your daughters lamentation, and \add every\add* woman teach her neighbour a dirge. 
\v 20 For death has come up through your windows, it has entered into our land, to destroy the infants outside, and the young men from the streets. 
\v 21 The carcases of the men will be for an example on the face of the field of your land, like grass after the mower, and there will be none to gather \add them\add*. 
\p
\v 22 Thus says the Lord, Don't let the wise man boast in his wisdom, and don't let the strong man boast in his strength, and don't let the rich man boast in his wealth; 
\v 23 but let him who boasts boast in this, the understanding and knowing that I am the Lord, I exercise mercy, and judgment, and righteousness, upon the earth; for in these things is my pleasure, says the Lord. 
\p
\v 24 Behold, days are coming, says the Lord, when I will visit upon all the circumcised their uncircumcision; 
\v 25 on Egypt, and on Idumea, and on Edom, and on the children of Ammon, and on the children of Moab, and on every one who shaves his face round about, \add even\add* those who dwell in the wilderness; for all the nations are uncircumcised in flesh, and all the house of Israel are uncircumcised \add in\add* their hearts. 
\c 10 
\p
\v 1 Hear the word of the Lord that he has spoken to you, O house of Israel. 
\p
\v 2 Thus says the Lord, Don't learn the ways of the nations, and don't be alarmed at the signs of the sky; for they are alarmed at them, \add falling\add* on their faces. 
\v 3 For the customs of the nations are vain; it is a tree cut out of the forest, the work of the carpenter, or a molten image. 
\v 4 \add They are\add* beautified with silver and gold, they fix them with hammers and nails; 
\v 5 they will set them up so they may not move; it is worked silver, they will not walk, 
\v 9 it is forged silver \add brought\add* from Tharsis, gold will come from Mophaz, and the work of goldsmiths: \add they are\add* all the works of craftsmen, they will clothe themselves with blue and scarlet. 
\v 9a They must certainly be carried, for they cannot ride \add of themselves\add*. Don't be afraid them; for they cannot do any evil, and there is no good in them. 
\p
\v 11 Thus you will say to them, Let the gods which have not made heaven and earth perish from off the earth, and from under this sky. 
\v 12 It is the Lord who made the earth by his strength, who set up the world by his wisdom, and by his understanding stretched out the sky, 
\v 13 and set abundance of waters in the sky, and brought up clouds from the ends of the earth; he made lightnings for the rain, and brought forth light out of his treasures. 
\v 14 Every man is deprived of knowledge, every goldsmith is greatly agitated because of his graven images; for he has cast false gods, there is no breath in them. 
\v 15 They are vain works, worked in mockery; in the time of their visitation they will perish. 
\v 16 Such isn't the portion of Jacob; for he who formed all things, he is his inheritance; the Lord is his name. 
\p
\v 17 He has gathered your possessions from outside, you who dwell among choice things. 
\v 18 For thus says the Lord, Behold, I \add will\add* overthrow the inhabitants of this land with affliction, that your plague may be uncovered. 
\p
\v 19 Alas for your ruin! Your plague is grievous: and I said, Surely this is your wound, and it has overtaken you. 
\v 20 Your tent is in a ruinous state, it has perished; and all your curtains have been torn apart: my children and my cattle are no more: there is no more any place for my tent, \add nor\add* place for my curtains. 
\v 21 For the shepherds have become foolish, and have not sought the Lord; therefore the whole pasture has failed, and \add the sheep\add* have been scattered. 
\v 22 Behold, there comes a sound of a noise, and a great earthquake from the land of the north, to make the cities of Judah a desolation, and a resting-place for ostriches. 
\p
\v 23 I know, O Lord, that man's way isn't his own; neither will a man go, and direct his going. 
\v 24 Chasten us, O Lord, but with judgment; and not in wrath, lest you make us few. 
\v 25 Pour out your wrath upon the nations that have not known you, and upon the families that have not called upon your name: for they have devoured Jacob, and consumed him, and have made his pasture desolate. 
\c 11 
\p
\v 1 The word that came to Jeremiah from the Lord, saying, 
\p
\v 2 Hear the words of this covenant. You will speak to the men of Judah, and to the dwellers in Jerusalem; 
\v 3 and you will say to them, Thus says the Lord God of Israel, Cursed is the man, who will not listen to the words of this covenant, 
\v 4 which I commanded your fathers, in the day when I brought them up out of the land of Egypt, out of the iron furnace, saying, Listen to my voice, and do all the things that I command you; so will you my people, and I will be your God; 
\v 5 that I may confirm my oath, which I swore to your fathers, to give them a land flowing \add with\add* milk and honey, as \add it is\add* this day. Then I answered and said, So be it, O Lord. 
\v 6 The Lord said to me, Read these words in the cities of Judah, and in the streets of Jerusalem, saying, Hear the words of this covenant, and do them. 
\v 8 But they did not do them. 
\p
\v 9 The Lord said to me, A conspiracy is found among the men of Judah, and among the dwellers in Jerusalem. 
\v 10 They are turned \add aside\add* to the iniquities of their fathers who were of old, who would not listen to my words: and, behold, they go after foreign gods, to serve them: and the house of Israel and the house of Judah have broken my covenant, which I made with their fathers. 
\p
\v 11 Therefore thus says the Lord, Behold, I bring evils upon this people, out of which they will not be able to come forth; and they will presently cry to me, but I will not listen to them. 
\v 12 The cities of Judah and the dwellers in Jerusalem will go, and cry to the gods to whom they burn incense; which will not deliver them in the time of their troubles. 
\v 13 For according to the number of your cities were your gods, O Judah; and according to the number of the streets of Jerusalem have you set up altars to burn incense to Baal. 
\p
\v 14 Now you, don't pray for this people, and don't intercede for them in supplication and prayer: for I will not hear in the day in which they call upon me, in the day of their affliction. 
\v 15 Why has \add my\add* beloved worked abomination in my house? Will prayers and holy offerings take away your wickedness from you, or will you escape by these things? 
\v 16 The Lord called your name a fair olive tree, of a goodly shade in appearance, at the noise of its being lopped, fire was kindled against it; great is the affliction \add coming\add* upon you: her branches have become good for nothing. 
\v 17 The Lord who planted you has pronounced evils against you, because of the wickedness of the house of Israel and the house of Judah, whatever they have done against themselves to provoke me to anger by burning incense to Baal. 
\p
\v 18 O Lord, teach me, and I will know: then I saw their practices. 
\v 19 But I as an innocent lamb led to the slaughter, didn't know: against me they devised an evil plan, saying, Come and let us put wood into his bread, and let us completely destroy him from off the land of the living, and let his name not be remembered any more. 
\v 20 O Lord, you who judge righteously, trying the reins and hearts, let me see your vengeance \add taken\add* upon them, for to you I have declared my cause. 
\p
\v 21 Therefore thus says the Lord concerning the men of Anathoth, that seek my life, that say, You will surely not prophesy in the name of the Lord, but if you do, you will die by our hands: 
\v 22 behold, I will visit them: their young men will die by the sword; and their sons and their daughters will die of famine: 
\v 23 and there will be no remnant \add left\add* of them; for I will bring evil upon the dwellers in Anathoth, in the year of their visitation. 
\c 12 
\p
\v 1 You are righteous, O Lord, that I may make my defence to you, yes, I will speak to you \add of\add* judgments. Why \add is it\add* that the way of ungodly \add men\add* prospers? \add that\add* all that deal very treacherously are flourishing? 
\v 2 You have planted them, and they have taken root; they have begotten children, and become fruitful; you are near to their mouth, and far from their reins. 
\v 3 But you, Lord, know me; you have proved my heart before you; purify them for the day of their slaughter. 
\v 4 How long will the land mourn, and the grass of the field wither, for the wickedness of those who dwell in it? The beasts and birds are completely destroyed; because \add the people\add* said, God will not see our ways. 
\p
\v 5 Your feet run, and they cause you to faint; how will you prepare \add to ride\add* upon horses? And you have been confident in the land of your peace? How will you do in the roaring of Jordan? 
\v 6 For even your brothers and the house of your father, even these have dealt treacherously with you; and they have cried out, they are gathered together in pursuit of you; don't trust in them, though they will speak fair \add words\add* to you. 
\p
\v 7 I have forsaken my house, I have left my heritage; I have given my beloved one into the hands of her enemies. 
\v 8 My inheritance has become to me like a lion in a forest; she has uttered her voice against me; therefore I have hated her. 
\v 9 Isn't my inheritance to me a hyena's cave, or a cave round about her? Go, gather together all the wild beasts of the field, and let them come to devour her. 
\p
\v 10 Many shepherds have destroyed my vineyard, they have defiled my portion, they have made my desirable portion a trackless wilderness; 
\v 11 it is made a complete ruin: for my sake the whole land has been completely ruined, because there is no one who lays \add the matter\add* to heart. 
\v 12 The ravagers have come to every passage in the wilderness: for the sword of the Lord will devour from one end of the land to the other: no flesh has any peace. 
\v 13 Sow wheat, and reap thorns; their portions will not profit them: be ashamed of your boasting, because of reproach before the Lord. 
\p
\v 14 For thus says the Lord concerning all the evil neighbours who touch my inheritance, which I have divided to my people Israel; Behold, I \add will\add* draw them away from their land, and I will cast out Judah from the midst of them. 
\p
\v 15 It will come to pass, after I have cast them out, \add that\add* I will return, and have mercy upon them, and will cause them to dwell every one in his inheritance, and every one in his land. 
\v 16 It will be, if they will indeed learn the way of my people, to swear by my name, \add saying\add*, The Lord lives; as they taught my people to swear by Baal; then \add that nation\add* will be built among my people. 
\v 17 But if they will not return, then will I cut off that nation with utter ruin and destruction. 
\c 13 
\p
\v 1 Thus says the Lord, Go and procure for yourself a linen girdle, and put it about your loins, and don't let it be put in water. 
\v 2 So I procured the girdle according to the word of the Lord, and put it about my loins. 
\v 3 The word of the Lord came to me, saying, 
\v 4 Take the girdle that is upon your loins, and arise, and go to the Euphrates, and hide it there in a hole of the rock. 
\v 5 So I went, and hid it by the Euphrates, as the Lord commanded me. 
\v 6 It happened after many days, that the Lord said to me, Arise, go to the Euphrates, and take from there the girdle, which I commanded you to hide there. 
\v 7 So I went to the river Euphrates, and dug, and took the girdle out of the place where I \add had\add* buried it: and, behold, it was rotten, completely good for nothing. 
\p
\v 8 The word of the Lord came to me, saying, Thus says the Lord, 
\v 9 Thus I will mar the pride of Judah, and the pride of Jerusalem; 
\v 10 \add even\add* this great pride \add of the men\add* who will not listen to my words, and have gone after foreign gods, to serve them, and to worship them: and they will be like this girdle, which can be used for nothing. 
\v 11 For as a girdle clings about the loins of a man, so have I caused to cling to myself the house of Israel, and the whole house of Judah; that they might be to me a famous people, and a praise, and a glory: but they did not listen to me. 
\p
\v 12 You will say to this people, Every wine-skin will be filled with wine: and it will come to pass, when they say to you, Don't we already know that every wine-skin will be filled with wine? That you will say to them, 
\v 13 Thus says the Lord, Behold, I \add will\add* fill the inhabitants of this land, and their kings the sons of David who sit upon their throne, and the priests, and the prophets, and Judah and all the dwellers in Jerusalem, with strong drink. 
\v 14 I will scatter them a man and his brother, and their fathers and their sons together: I will not have compassion, says the Lord, and I will not spare, neither will I pity \add to save them\add* from destruction. 
\p
\v 15 Hear, and give ear, and don't be proud: for the Lord has spoken. 
\v 16 Give glory to the Lord your God, before he causes darkness, and before your feet stumble on the dark mountains; and you will wait for light, and behold the shadow of death, and they will be brought into darkness. 
\v 17 But if you will not listen, your soul will weep in secret because of pride, and your eyes will pour down tears, because the Lord's flock is sorely bruised. 
\p
\v 18 Say to the king and the princes, Humble yourselves, and sit down; for your crown of glory is removed from your head. 
\v 19 The cities toward the south were shut, and there was none to open \add them\add*: Judah is removed \add into captivity\add*, they have suffered a complete removal. 
\v 20 Lift up your eyes, O Jerusalem, and behold those who come from the north; where is the flock that was given you, the sheep of your glory? 
\v 21 What will you say when they will come upon you, for you yourself taught them to rule over you; will not pains seize you like a woman in labor? 
\v 22 If you should say in your heart, Why have these things happened to me? Because of the abundance of your wickedness your \f + \fr 13:22 \fqa Gr. \ft rear parts.\f*nakedness has been uncovered; your heels laid bare in disgrace. 
\p
\v 23 If the Ethiopian will change his skin, or the leopardess her spots, then will you be able to do good, having learnt evil. 
\v 24 So I scattered them as sticks carried by the wind into the wilderness. 
\v 25 Thus is your lot, and the reward of your disobedience to me, says the Lord; as you did forget me, and trust in lies, 
\v 26 I also will expose your skirts upon your face, and your shame will be seen; 
\v 27 your adultery also, and your neighing, and the looseness of your prostitution: on the hills and in the fields I have seen your abominations. Woe to you, O Jerusalem, for you have not been purified so as to follow me; how long yet \add will it be\add*? 
\c 14 
\d
\v 1 \sc The Word of the Lord came to Jeremiah concerning the Drought.\sc* 
\p
\v 2 Judea has mourned, and her gates are emptied, and are darkened upon the earth; and the cry of Jerusalem has gone up. 
\v 3 Her nobles have sent their little ones to the water: they came to the wells, and found no water: and brought back their vessels empty. 
\v 4 The labours of the land failed, because there was no rain: the farmers were ashamed, they covered their heads. 
\v 5 Hinds calved in the field, and abandoned \add it\add*, because there was no grass. 
\v 6 The wild donkeys stood by the forests, and snuffed up the wind; their eyes failed, because there was no grass. 
\p
\v 7 Our sins have risen up against us: O Lord, do for us for your own sake; for our sins are many before you; for we have sinned against you. 
\v 8 O Lord, \add you are\add* the hope of Israel, and deliver \add us\add* in time of troubles; why have you become as a sojourner upon the land, or as one born in the land, yet turning aside for a resting-place? 
\v 9 Will you be as a man asleep, or as a \add strong\add* man who cannot save? Yet you are among us, O Lord, and your name is called on us; don't forget us. 
\p
\v 10 Thus says the Lord to this people, They have loved to wander, and they have not spared, therefore God has not prospered them; now he will remember their wickedness. 
\v 11 The Lord said to me, Don't pray for this people for \add their\add* good: 
\v 12 for though they fast, I will not hear their supplication; and though they offer whole-burnt-offerings and sacrifices, I will take no pleasure in them: for I will consume them with sword, and with famine, and with pestilence. 
\p
\v 13 I said, O \add ever\add* living Lord! Behold, their prophets prophesy, and say, You will not see a sword, nor will famine be among you; for I will give truth and peace on the land, and in this place. 
\p
\v 14 Then the Lord said to me, The prophets prophesy lies in my name: I didn't send them, and I didn't command them, and I didn't speak to them: for they prophesy to you false visions, and divinations, and auguries, and devices of their own heart. 
\v 15 Therefore thus says the Lord concerning the prophets who prophesy lies in my name, and I didn't send them, who say, Sword and famine will not be upon this land; they will die by a grievous death, and the prophets will be consumed by famine. 
\v 16 The people to whom they prophesy, they also will be cast out in the streets of Jerusalem, because of the sword and famine; and there will be none to bury them: their wives also, and their sons, and their daughters \add will die thus\add*; and I will pour out their wickedness upon them. 
\p
\v 17 You will speak this word to them; Let your eyes shed tears day and night, and don't let them cease: for the daughter of my people has been sorely bruised, and her plague is very grievous. 
\v 18 If I go forth into the plain, then behold the killed by the sword! And if I enter into the city, then behold the distress of famine! For priest and prophet have gone to a land which they didn't know. 
\p
\v 19 Have you completely rejected Judah? And has your soul departed from Zion? Why have you struck us, and there is no healing for us? We waited for peace, but there was no prosperity; for a time of healing, and behold trouble! 
\v 20 We know, O Lord, our sins, \add and\add* the iniquities of our fathers: for we have sinned before you. 
\v 21 Refrain for your name's sake, don't destroy the throne of your glory: remember, don't break your covenant with us. 
\v 22 Is there any one among the idols of the nations that can give rain? And will the sky yield his fulness \add at their bidding\add*? Are you not he? We will even wait on you, O Lord: for you have made all these things. 
\c 15 
\p
\v 1 The Lord said to me, Though Moses and Samuel stood before my face, I would have no regard for them: send this people away, let them go.
\v 2 It will be, if they say to you, Where will we go? Then you will say to them, Thus says the Lord; Those \add destined\add* for death, to death; and those for famine, to famine; and those for the sword, to the sword; and those for captivity, to captivity. 
\v 3 I will punish them with four kinds \add of death\add*, says the Lord, the sword to kill, and the dogs to tear, and the wild beasts of the earth, and the birds of the sky to devour and destroy. 
\v 4 I will deliver them up for distress to all the kingdoms of the earth, because of Manasseh son of Hezekiah king of Judah, for all that he did in Jerusalem. 
\p
\v 5 Who will spare you, O Jerusalem? And who will fear for you? Or who will turn back \add to ask\add* for your welfare? 
\v 6 You have turned away from me, says the Lord, you keep going backward: therefore I will stretch out my hand and destroy you, and will no longer spare them. 
\v 7 I will completely scatter them; in the gates of my people they are bereaved of children: they have destroyed my people because of their iniquities. 
\p
\v 8 Their widows have been multiplied more than the sand of the sea: I have brought young men against the mother, \add even\add* distress at noon-day: I have suddenly cast upon her trembling and anxiety. 
\v 9 The one who bore seven is spent; her soul has fainted under trouble; her sun is gone down while it is yet noon; she is ashamed and disgraced: I will give the remnant of them to the sword before their enemies. 
\p
\v 10 Woe is me, \add my\add* mother! What kind of man have you given birth to me, a man in dispute and contention with all the land? I have not helped \add others\add*, nor has any one helped me; my strength has failed among those who curse me. 
\v 11 So be it, Lord, even in their prosperity; surely I stood before you in the time of their calamities, and in the time of their affliction, for \add their\add* good against the enemy. 
\v 12 Can iron be broken? Or a covering of bronze?
\v 13 Yes, I will give your treasures for a spoil as a recompence, because of all your sins, and \add that\add* in all your borders. 
\v 14 I will enslave you to your enemies round about, in a land which you have not known; for a fire has been kindled out of my wrath; it will burn upon you. 
\p
\v 15 O Lord, remember me, and visit me, and vindicate me before those who persecute me; do not bear long with them; know how I have met with reproach for your sake, from those who despise your words; 
\v 16 consume them; and your word will be to me for the joy and gladness of my heart: for your name has been called upon me, O Lord Almighty. 
\v 17 I have not sat in the assembly of them as they mocked, but I feared because of your power: I sat alone, for I was filled with bitterness. 
\p
\v 18 Why do those who grieve me prevail against me? My wound is severe; how will I be healed? It has indeed become to me as deceitful water, that cannot be trusted.
\p
\v 19 Therefore thus says the Lord, If you will return, then will I restore you, and you will stand before my face: and if you will bring forth the precious from the worthless, you will be as my mouth: and they will return to you; but you will not return to them. 
\v 20 I will make you to this people as a strong bronze wall; and they will fight against you, but they will by no means prevail against you; 
\v 21 for I am with you to save you, and to deliver you out of the hand of wicked \add men\add*; and I will ransom you out of the hand of pestilent \add men\add*. 
\c 16 
\p
\v 1 You will not take a wife, says the Lord God of Israel: 
\v 2 and there will be no son born to you, nor daughter in this place. 
\v 3 For thus says the Lord concerning the sons and concerning the daughters who are born in this place, and concerning their mothers who have given birth to them, and concerning their fathers who have begotten them in this land; 
\v 4 They will die of grievous death; they will not be lamented, nor buried; they will be for an example on the face of the earth; and they will be for the wild beasts of the land, and for the birds of the sky: they will fall by the sword, and will be consumed with famine. 
\p
\v 5 Thus says the Lord, Don't enter into their mourning feast, and don't go to lament, and don't mourn for them: for I have removed my peace from this people. 
\v 6 They will not bewail them, nor make cuttings for them, and they will not shave themselves \add for them\add*: 
\v 7 and there will be no bread broken in mourning for them for consolation over the dead: they will not give one to drink a cup for consolation over his father or his mother. 
\p
\v 8 You will not enter into the banquet-house, to sit with them to eat and to drink. 
\v 9 For thus says the Lord God of Israel; Behold, before your eyes and in your days I \add will\add* make an end to the voice of joy, and the voice of gladness, the voice of the bridegroom, and the voice of the bride. 
\p
\v 10 It will come to pass, when you will report to this people all these words, and they will say to you, Why has the Lord pronounced against us all these evils? What is our unrighteousness? And what is our sin which we have sinned before the Lord our God? 
\v 11 Then you will say to them, Because your fathers forsook me, says the Lord, and went after foreign gods and served them, and worshipped them, and forsook me, and didn't keep my law; 
\v 12 (and you sinned worse than your fathers; for, behold, you walk every one after the lusts of your own evil heart, so as not to listen to me); 
\v 13 therefore I will cast you off from this good land into a land which neither you nor your fathers have known; and you will serve there other gods, who will have no mercy upon you. 
\p
\v 14 Therefore, behold, days are coming, says the Lord, when they will no more say, The Lord lives, who brought the children of Israel up out of the land of Egypt; 
\v 15 but, The Lord lives, who brought the house of Israel up from the land of the north, and from all the lands where they were thrust out: and I will restore them to their own land, which I gave to their fathers. 
\p
\v 16 Behold, I \add will\add* send many fishers, says the Lord, and they will fish them; and afterward I will send many hunters, and they will hunt them upon every mountain, and upon every hill, and out of the holes of the rocks. 
\v 17 For my eyes are upon all their ways; and their iniquities have not been hidden from my eyes. 
\v 18 I will repay them double for their iniquities, and their sins, by which they have profaned my land with the carcases of their abominations, and with their iniquities, by which they have trespassed against my inheritance. 
\p
\v 19 O Lord, you are my strength, and my help, and my refuge in days of evil: to you the nations will come from the end of the earth, and will say, How vain \add were the\add* idols \add which\add* our fathers procured to themselves, and there is no help in them. 
\v 20 Will a man make gods for himself, because these are no gods? 
\v 21 Therefore, behold, I will at this time show my hand to them, and will make known to them my power; and they will know that my name is the Lord. 
\c 17 
\p
\v 5 Cursed is the man who puts his hope in man, and makes human strength his support, and whose heart departs from the Lord. 
\v 6 He will be as the wild tamarisk in the desert: he will not see when good comes; but he will dwell in barren \add places\add*, and in the wilderness, in a salt land which isn't inhabited. 
\v 7 But blessed is the man who trusts in the Lord, and the Lord will be his hope.
\v 8 He will be as a thriving tree by the waters, and he will cast forth his root toward a moist place: he will not fear when heat comes, and there will be shady branches on him: he will not fear in a year of drought, and he will not fail to bear fruit. 
\p
\v 9 The heart is deep beyond all things, and it is human, and who can understand it? 
\v 10 I the Lord try the hearts, and prove the reins, to give to every one according to his ways, and according to the fruits of his devices. 
\p
\v 11 The partridge utters her voice, she gathers \add eggs\add* which she did not lay; \add so is a man\add* gaining his wealth unjustly; among his days \add his riches\add* will leave him, and at his latter end he will be a fool. 
\p
\v 12 An exalted throne of glory is our sanctuary. 
\v 13 O Lord, the hope of Israel, let all who have left you be shamed, let those who have revolted be written on the earth, because they have forsaken the Lord, the fountain of life.
\p
\v 14 Heal me, O Lord, and I will be healed; save me, and I will be saved; for you are my boast. 
\p
\v 15 Behold, they say to me, Where is the word of the Lord? Let it come. 
\v 16 But I have not been weary of following you, nor have I desired the day of man; you know; the \add words\add* that proceed out of my lips are before your face. 
\v 17 Don't be to me a stranger, \add but\add* spare me in the evil day. 
\v 18 Let those who persecute me be shamed, but don't let me be shamed: let them be alarmed, but don't let me be alarmed: bring upon them the evil day, crush them with double destruction. 
\p
\v 19 Thus says the Lord; Go and stand in the gates of the children of your people, by which the kings of Judah enter, and by which they go out, and in all the gates of Jerusalem: 
\v 20 and you will say to them, Hear the word of the Lord, you kings of Judah, and all Judea, and all Jerusalem, \add all\add* who go in at these gates: 
\v 21 thus says the Lord; Take heed to your souls, and take up no burdens on the sabbath-day, and don't go forth \add through\add* the gates of Jerusalem; 
\v 22 and carry forth no burdens out of your houses on the sabbath-day, and you will do no work: sanctify the sabbath-day, as I commanded your fathers. 
\v 23 But they didn't listen, and didn't incline their ear, but stiffened their neck more than their fathers \add did\add*, so as not to hear me, and not to receive correction. 
\p
\v 24 It will come to pass, if you will listen to me, says the Lord, to carry in no burdens through the gates of this city on the sabbath-day, and to sanctify the sabbath-day, so as to do no work \add upon it\add*, 
\v 25 that there will enter through the gates of this city kings and princes sitting on the throne of David, and riding on their chariots and horses, they, and their princes, the men of Judah, and the dwellers in Jerusalem: and this city will be inhabited forever. 
\v 26 And \add men\add* will come out of the cities of Judah, and from around Jerusalem, and out of the land of Benjamin, and out of the plain country, and from the hill country, and from the south \add country\add*, bringing whole-burnt-offerings, and sacrifices, and incense, and manna, and frankincense, bringing praise to the house of the Lord. 
\p
\v 27 But it will come to pass, if you will not listen to me to sanctify the sabbath-day, to bear no burdens, nor go in \add with them by\add* the gates of Jerusalem on the sabbath-day; then will I kindle a fire in its gates, and it will devour the streets of Jerusalem, and will not be quenched. 
\c 18 
\p
\v 1 The word that came from the Lord to 
\v 2 Jeremiah, saying, Arise, and go down to the potter's house, and there you will hear my words. 
\v 3 So I went down to the potter's house, and behold, he was making a vessel on the stones. 
\v 4 The vessel which he was making with his hands fell: so he made it again another vessel, as it seemed good to him to make \add it\add*. 
\v 5 The word of the Lord came to me, saying, 
\p
\v 6 Will I not be able, O house of Israel, to do to you as this potter? Behold, you are like the clay of the potter in my hands. 
\v 7 \add If\add* I will pronounce a decree upon a nation, or upon a kingdom, to cut them off, and to destroy \add them\add*; 
\v 8 and that nation turns from all their sins, then I will repent of the evils which I planned to do to them. 
\v 9 And \add if\add* I will pronounce a decree upon a nation and kingdom, to rebuild and to plant \add it\add*; 
\v 10 and they do evil before me, so as not to listen to my voice, then I will repent of the good which I spoke of, to do it to them. 
\p
\v 11 Now say to the men of Judah, and to the inhabitants of Jerusalem, Behold, I prepare evils against you, and devise a plan against you: let every one turn now from his evil way, and amend your practices. 
\v 12 They said, We will aquit ourselves like men, for we will pursue our perverse ways, and we will each perform the lusts of his evil heart. 
\p
\v 13 Therefore thus says the Lord; Enquire now among the nations, who has heard such very horrible things as the virgin of Israel has done? 
\v 14 Will fertilising streams fail \add to flow\add* from a rock, or snow \add fail\add* from Lebanon? Will water violently impelled by the wind turn aside? 
\v 15 For my people have forgotten me, they have offered incense in vain, and they fail in their ways, \add leaving\add* the ancient tracks, to enter upon impassable paths; 
\v 16 to make their land a desolation, and a perpetual hissing; all who go through it will be amazed, and will shake their heads. 
\v 17 I will scatter them before their enemies like an east wind; I will show them the day of their destruction. 
\p
\v 18 Then they said, Come, and let us devise a plan against Jeremiah; for the law will not perish from the priest, nor counsel from the wise, nor the word from the prophet. Come, and let us strike him with the tongue, and we will hear all his words. 
\p
\v 19 Hear me, O Lord, and hear the voice of my pleading. 
\v 20 Although evil is rewarded for good; for they have spoken words against my soul, and they have hidden the punishment they \add meant\add* for me; remember that I stood before your face, to speak good for them, to turn away your wrath from them. 
\v 21 Therefore deliver their sons to famine, and gather them to the power of the sword: let their women be childless and widows; and let their men be cut off by death, and their young men fall by the sword in war. 
\v 22 Let there be a cry in their houses: you will bring robbers upon them suddenly: for they have formed a plan to take me, and have hidden snares for me. 
\p
\v 23 You, Lord, know all their deadly counsel against me: don't account their iniquities guiltless, and don't blot out their sins from before you: let their weakness come before you; deal with them in the time of your wrath. 
\c 19 
\p
\v 1 Then said the Lord to me, Go and get an earthen jar, the work of the potter, and you will bring \add some\add* of the elders of the people, and of the priests; 
\v 2 and you will go forth to the burial-place of the sons of their children, which is at the entrance of the gate of Charsith; and read there all these words which I will speak to you: 
\v 3 and you will say to them, 
\p Hear the word of the Lord, you kings of Judah, and men of Judah, and the dwellers in Jerusalem, and those who enter in by these gates; thus says the Lord God of Israel; Behold, I \add will\add* bring evil upon this place, so that the ears of every one who hears it will tingle. 
\v 4 Because they forsook me, and profaned this place, and burnt incense in it to foreign gods, which they and their fathers didn't know; and the kings of Judah have filled this place with innocent blood, 
\v 5 and built high places for Baal, to burn their children in the fire, which things I didn't command, neither did I design \add them\add* in my heart: 
\p
\v 6 Therefore, behold, the days are coming, says the Lord, when this place will no more be called, The fall and burial-place of the son of Ennom, but, The burial-place of slaughter. 
\v 7 I will destroy the counsel of Judah and the counsel of Jerusalem in this place; and I will cast them down with the sword before their enemies, and by the hands of those who seek their lives: and I will give their dead bodies for food to the birds of the sky and to the wild beasts of the earth. 
\v 8 I will bring this city to desolation and \add make it\add* a hissing; every one who passes by it will scowl, and hiss because of all her plague. 
\v 9 They will eat the flesh of their sons, and the flesh of their daughters; and they will eat every one the flesh of his neighbour in the blockade, and in the siege with which their enemies will besiege them. 
\p
\v 10 You will break the jar in the sight of the men who go forth with you, 
\v 11 and you will say, Thus says the Lord, Thus will I break in pieces this people, and this city, even as an earthen vessel is broken in pieces which cannot be mended again. 
\v 12 Thus will I do, says the Lord, to this place, and to the inhabitants of it, that this city may be given up, as one that is falling to ruin. 
\v 13 The houses of Jerusalem, and the houses of the kings of Judah will be as a ruinous place, because of their uncleannesses in all the houses, where they burnt incense upon their roofs to all the host of heaven, and poured drink-offerings to foreign gods. 
\p
\v 14 Jeremiah came from \add the place\add* of the Fall, where the Lord had sent him to prophesy; and he stood in the court of the Lord's house; and said to all the people, Thus says the Lord; 
\v 15 Behold, I bring upon this city, and upon all the cities belonging to it, and upon its villages, all the evils which I have spoken against it, because they have hardened their neck, \add that they might not\add* listen to my commands. 
\c 20 
\p
\v 1 Now Paschor the son of Emmer, the priest, who also had been appointed chief of the house of the Lord, heard Jeremiah prophesying these words. 
\v 2 He struck him, and cast him into the dungeon which was by the gate of the upper house that was set apart, which was by the house of the Lord. 
\p
\v 3 Paschor brought Jeremiah out of the dungeon: and Jeremiah said to him, \add The Lord\add* has not called your name Paschor, but Exile. 
\v 4 For thus says the Lord, Behold, I \add will\add* give you up to captivity with all your friends: and they will fall by the sword of their enemies, and your eyes will see \add it\add*: and I will give you and all Judah into the hands of the king of Babylon, and they will carry them as captives, and cut them in pieces with swords. 
\v 5 I will give all the strength of this city, and all the labours of it, and all the treasures of the king of Judah, into the hands of his enemies, and they will bring them to Babylon. 
\v 6 You and all the dwellers in your house will go into captivity: and you will die in Babylon, and there you and all your friends will be buried, to whom you have prophesied lies. 
\p
\v 7 You have deceived me, O Lord, and I have been deceived: you have been strong, and have prevailed: I have become a laughing-stock, I am continually mocked every day. 
\v 8 For I will laugh with my bitter speech, I will call upon rebellion and misery: for the word of the Lord has become a reproach to me and a mockery all my days. 
\v 9 Then I said, I will by no means name the name of the Lord, and I will surely not speak in his name any more. But it was as burning fire flaming in my bones, and I am completely weakened on all sides, and cannot bear \add up\add*. 
\v 10 For I have heard the reproach of many gathering round, \add saying\add*, Conspire, and let us conspire together against him, \add even\add* all his friends: watch his intentions, if perhaps he will be deceived, and we will prevail against him, and we will be avenged on him. 
\p
\v 11 But the Lord was with me as a mighty man of war: therefore they persecuted \add me\add*, but could not perceive \add anything against me\add*; they were greatly greatly agitated, for they didn't perceive their disgrace, which will never be forgotten. 
\p
\v 12 O Lord, you who prove just \add deeds\add*, understanding the reins and hearts, let me see your vengeance upon them: for to you I have revealed my cause. 
\v 13 Sing to the Lord, sing praise to him: for he has rescued the soul of the poor from the hand of evil-doers. 
\p
\v 14 Cursed be the day in which I was born: the day when my mother brought me forth, don't let it be blessed. 
\v 15 Cursed be the man who brought the glad tidings to my father, saying, A male child is born to you. 
\v 16 Let that man rejoice as the cities which the Lord overthrew in wrath, and didn't repent: let him hear crying in the morning, and loud lamentation at noon; 
\v 17 because he didn't kill me in the womb, and my mother didn't became my tomb, and her womb always great with me. 
\v 18 Why is it that I came forth from the womb to see troubles and distresses, and my days are spent in shame? 
\c 21 
\p
\v 1 \sc The Word that came from the Lord to Jeremiah, when King Zedekiah sent to him Paschor the Son of Melchias, and Zephaniah Son of Basæas, the Priest, saying,\sc* 
\p
\v 2 Enquire of the Lord for us; for the king of Babylon has risen up against us; if the Lord will do according to all his wonderful works, and \add the king\add* will depart from us. 
\p
\v 3 Jeremiah said to them, Thus will you say to Zedekiah king of Judah, 
\v 4 Thus says the Lord; Behold, I \add will\add* turn back the weapons of war with which you fight against the Chaldeans who have besieged you from outside the wall, and I will gather them into the midst of this city. 
\v 5 I will fight against you with an outstretched hand and with a strong arm, with wrath and great anger. 
\v 6 I will strike all the dwellers in this city, \add both\add* men and cattle, with grievous pestilence: and they will die. 
\v 7 After this, thus says the Lord; I will give Zedekiah king of Judah, and his servants, and the people who are left in this city from the pestilence, and from the famine, and from the sword, into the hands of their enemies who seek their lives: and they will cut them in pieces with the edge of the sword: I will not spare them, and I will not have compassion upon them. 
\p
\v 8 You will say to this people, Thus says the Lord; Behold, I have set before you the way of life, and the way of death. 
\v 9 He who remains in this city will die by the sword, and by famine: but he who goes forth to advance to the Chaldeans who have besieged you, will live, and his life will be to him for a spoil, and he will live. 
\v 10 For I have set my face against this city for evil, and not for good: it will be delivered into the hands of the king of Babylon, and he will consume it with fire. 
\p
\v 11 O house of the king of Judah, hear the word of the Lord. 
\v 12 O house of David, thus says the Lord; Judge judgment in the morning, and act rightly, and rescue the spoiled one from the hand of the one who wrongs him, lest my anger be kindled like fire, and it burn, and there be none to quench \add it\add*. 
\v 13 Behold, I am against you who dwell in the valley of Sor; in the plain country, \add even against\add* those who say, Who will alarm us? Or who will enter into our habitation? 
\v 14 I will kindle a fire in the forest of it, and it will devour all things round about it. 
\c 22 
\p
\v 1 Thus says the Lord; Go, go down to the house of the king of Judah, and you will speak there this word, 
\v 2 and you will say, 
\p Hear the word of the Lord, O king of Judah, who sits on the throne of David, you, and your house, and your people, and those who go in at these gates: 
\v 3 thus says the Lord; Execute judgment and justice, and rescue the spoiled out of the hand of the one who wrongs him: and don't oppress the stranger, and orphan, and widow, and don't sin, and shed no innocent blood in this place. 
\v 4 For if you will indeed perform this word, then will there enter in by the gates of this house kings sitting upon the throne of David, and riding on chariots and horses, they, and their servants, and their people. 
\v 5 But if you will not perform these words, by myself I have sworn, says the Lord, that this house will be \add brought\add* to desolation. 
\p
\v 6 For thus says the Lord concerning the house of the king of Judah; You are Gilead to me, \add and\add* the head of Lebanon: \add yet\add* surely I will make you a desert, \add even\add* cities that will not be inhabited: 
\v 7 and I will bring upon you a destroying man, and his axe: and they will cut down your choice cedars, and cast \add them\add* into the fire. 
\v 8 Nations will pass through this city, and each will say to his neighbour, Why has the Lord done thus to this great city? 
\v 9 They will say, Because they forsook the covenant of the Lord their God, and worshipped foreign gods, and served them. 
\p
\v 10 Don't weep for the dead, nor lament for him: weep bitterly for him who goes away: for he will return no more, nor see his native land. 
\v 11 For thus says the Lord concerning Sellem the son of Josiah, who reigns in the place of Josiah his father, who has gone forth out of this place; He will not return there any more: 
\v 12 but in that place where I have carried him captive, there he will die, and will see this land no more. 
\p
\v 13 He who doesn't build his house with justice, nor his upper chambers with judgment, who works by means of his neighbour for nothing, and will by no means give him his reward. 
\v 14 You have built for yourself a well-proportioned house, airy chambers, fitted with windows, and wainscoted with cedar, and painted with vermilion. 
\v 15 Will you reign, because you are provoked with your father Ahaz? They will not eat, and they will not drink: it is better for you to execute judgment and justice. 
\v 16 They didn't understand, they didn't judge the cause of the afflicted, nor the cause of the poor: isn't this your not knowing me? Says the Lord. 
\v 17 Behold, your eyes are not good, nor your heart, but \add they go\add* after your covetousness, and after the innocent blood to shed it, and after acts of injustice and slaughter, to commit them. 
\p
\v 18 Therefore thus says the Lord concerning Joakim son of Josiah, king of Judah, even concerning this man; they will not bewail him, \add saying\add*, Ah brother! Neither will they at all weep for him, \add saying\add*, Alas Lord. 
\v 19 He will be buried with the burial of an ass; he will be dragged roughly along and cast outside the gate of Jerusalem. 
\p
\v 20 Go up to Lebanon, and cry; and utter your voice to Basan, and cry aloud to the extremity of the sea: for all your lovers are destroyed. 
\v 21 I spoke to you on \add occasion of\add* your trespass, but you said, I will not listen. This \add has been\add* your way from your youth, you have not listened to my voice. 
\v 22 The wind will tend all your shepherds, and your lovers will go into captivity; for then will you be shamed and disgraced because of all your lovers. 
\v 23 O you who dwell in Lebanon, making your nest in the cedars, you will groan heavily, when pains as of a woman in labour have come upon you. 
\p
\v 24 \add As\add* I live, says the Lord, though Jechonias son of Joakim king of Judah were indeed the seal upon my right hand, from there would I pluck you; 
\v 25 and I will deliver you into the hands of those who seek your life, before whom you are afraid, into the hands of the Chaldeans. 
\v 26 I will cast forth you, and your mother who bore you, into a land where you were not born; and there you will die. 
\v 27 But they will by no means return to the land which they long for in their souls. 
\v 28 Jechonias is dishonoured as a good-for-nothing vessel; for he is thrown out and cast forth into a land which he didn't know. 
\p
\v 29 Land, land, hear the word of the Lord. 
\v 30 Write this man disqualified: for surely none of his seed will grow up to sit on the throne of David, \add or as\add* a prince yet in Judah. 
\c 23 
\p
\v 1 Woe to the shepherds who destroy and scatter the sheep of their pasture! 
\v 2 Therefore thus says the Lord against those who tend my people; You have scattered my sheep, and driven them out, and you have not visited them: behold, I \add will\add* take vengeance upon you according to your evil practices. 
\v 3 I will gather in the remnant of my people in every land, where I have driven them out, and will set them in their pasture; and they will increase and be multiplied. 
\v 4 I will raise up shepherds for them, who will feed them: and they will fear no more, nor be alarmed, says the Lord. 
\p
\v 5 Behold, days are coming, says the Lord, when I will raise up for David a righteous branch, and a king will reign and understand, and will execute judgment and righteousness on the earth. 
\v 6 In his days both Judah will be saved, and Israel will dwell securely: and this is his name, which the Lord will call him: \f + \fr 23:6 \fqa Gr. \ft transliterates a Hebrew name meaning “The Lord is righteous.”\f*Josedec.
\p
\v 9  Among the prophets my heart is broken within me; all my bones are shaken: I have become as a broken-down man, and as a man overcome with wine, because of the Lord, and because of the excellence of his glory. 
\v 10 For because of these things the land mourns; the pastures of the wilderness are dried up; and their course has become evil, and so \add also\add* their strength. 
\v 11 For priest and prophet are defiled; and I have seen their iniquities in my house. 
\v 12 Therefore let their way be to them slippery and dark: and they will be tripped up and fall in it: for I will bring evils upon them, in the year of their visitation. 
\p
\v 13 In the prophets of Samaria I have seen lawless deeds; they prophesied by Baal, and led my people Israel astray. 
\v 14 Also in the prophets of Jerusalem I have seen horrible things: as they committed adultery, and walked in lies, and strengthened the hands of many, that they should not return each from his evil way: they are all become to me as Sodom, and the inhabitants of it as Gomorrah. 
\p
\v 15 Therefore thus says the Lord; Behold, I will feed them with pain, and give them bitter water to drink: for from the prophets of Jerusalem has defilement gone forth \add into\add* all the land. 
\p
\v 16 Thus says the Lord Almighty, Don't listen to the words of the prophets: for they frame a vain vision for themselves; they speak from their own heart, and not from the mouth of the Lord. 
\v 17 They say to those who reject the word of the Lord, There will be peace to you; and to all who walk after their own lusts, and to every one who walks in the error of his heart, they have said, No evil will come upon you. 
\v 18 For who has stood in the counsel of the Lord, and seen his word? Who has listened, and heard? 
\v 19 Behold, \add there is\add* an earthquake from the Lord, and anger proceeds to a convulsion, it will come violently upon the ungodly. 
\v 20 The Lord's wrath will return no more, until he has accomplished it, and until he has established it, according to the purpose of his heart: at the end of the days they will understand it. 
\p
\v 21 I didn't send the prophets, yet they ran: I didn't speak to them, yet they prophesied. 
\v 22 But if they had stood in my counsel, and if they had listened to my words, then would they have turned my people from their evil practices. 
\p
\v 23 I am a God near at hand, says the Lord, and not a God afar off. 
\v 24 Will any one hide himself in secret places, and I not see him? Do I not fill heaven and earth? Says the Lord. 
\p
\v 25 I have heard what the prophets say, what they prophesy in my name, saying falsely, I have seen a night vision. 
\v 26 How long will \add these things\add* be in the heart of the prophets who prophesy lies, when they prophesy the purposes of their own heart? 
\v 27 who devise that \add men\add* may forget my law by their dreams, which they have told every one to his neighbour, as their fathers forgot my name in \add the worship of\add* Baal. 
\v 28 The prophet who has a dream, let him tell his dream; and \add he\add* in whom is my word \add spoken\add* to him, let him tell my word truly: what is the chaff to the grain? So are my words, says the Lord. 
\v 29 Behold, are not my words as fire? Says the Lord; and as an axe cutting the rock? 
\p
\v 30 Behold, I am therefore against the prophets, says the Lord God, who steal my words every one from his neighbour. 
\v 31 Behold, I am against the prophets who put forth prophecies of mere words, and slumber their sleep. 
\v 32 Therefore, behold, I am against the prophets who prophesy false dreams, and have not told them \add truly\add*, and have caused my people to err by their lies, and by their errors; yet I didn't send them, and didn't command them; therefore, they will not profit this people at all. 
\p
\v 33 If this people, or the priest, or the prophet, should ask, What is the message from the Lord? Then you will say to them, You are the message, and I will dash you down, says the Lord. 
\v 34 \add As for\add* the prophet, and the priests, and the people, who will say, The message of the Lord, I will even take vengeance on that man, and on his house. 
\v 35 Thus will you say every one to his neighbour, and every one to his brother, What has the Lord answered? And, what has the Lord said? 
\v 36 Name no more the message of the Lord; for his own word will be a man's message. 
\v 37 But why, \add you say\add*, has the Lord our God spoken? 
\v 38 Therefore thus says the Lord our God; Because you have spoken this word, The message from the Lord, and I sent to you, saying, You will not say, The message of the Lord; 
\v 39 therefore, behold, I \add will\add* seize, and dash down you and the city which I gave to you and your fathers. 
\v 40 I will bring upon you an everlasting reproach, and everlasting disgrace, which will not be forgotten. 
\p
\v 40a \x + \xo 23:40a--40b \xt Jer 16:14--15\x*Therefore, behold, days are coming, says the Lord, when they will no more say, The Lord lives, who brought up the house of Israel out of the land of Egypt; 
\v 40b but The Lord lives, who has gathered the whole seed of Israel from the north land, and from all the lands where he \add had\add* driven them out, and has restored them into their own land. 
\c 24 
\p
\v 1 The Lord showed me two baskets of figs, lying in front of the temple of the Lord, after Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon had carried captive Jechonias son of Joakim king of Judah, and the princes, and the craftsmen, and the prisoners, and the rich men out of Jerusalem, and had brought them to Babylon. 
\v 2 The one basket was \add full\add* of very good figs, as the early figs; and the other basket was \add full\add* of very bad figs, which could not be eaten, for their badness. 
\v 3 The Lord said to me, What do you see, Jeremiah? And I said, Figs; the good figs, very good; and the bad, very bad, which cannot be eaten, for their badness. 
\p
\v 4 The word of the Lord came to me, saying, 
\v 5 Thus says the Lord, the God of Israel; As these good figs, so I will acknowledge the Jews who have been carried away captive, whom I have sent out of this place into the land of the Chaldeans for their good. 
\v 6 I will fix my eyes upon them for their good, and I will restore them into this land for their good: and I will build them up, and not pull them down; and I will plant them, and not pluck them up. 
\p
\v 7 I will give them a heart to know me, that I am the Lord: and they will be to me a people, and I will be to them a God: for they will turn to me with all their heart. 
\p
\v 8 As the bad figs, which cannot be eaten, for their badness; thus says the Lord, So will I deliver Zedekiah king of Judah, and his nobles, and the remnant of Jerusalem, those who are left in this land, and the dwellers in Egypt. 
\v 9 I will cause them to be dispersed into all the kingdoms of the earth, and they will be for a reproach, and a proverb, and an \add object of\add* hatred, and a curse, in every place where I have driven them out. 
\v 10 I will send against them famine, and pestilence, and the sword, until they are consumed from off the land which I gave them. 
\c 25 
\p
\v 1 \sc The Word that came to Jeremiah\sc* concerning all the people of Judah in the fourth year of Joakim, son of Josiah, king of Judah; 
\v 2 which he spoke to all the people of Judah, and to the inhabitants of Jerusalem, saying, 
\p
\v 3 In the thirteenth year of Josiah, son of Amos, king of Judah, even until this day for twenty-three years I have both spoken to you, rising early and speaking, 
\v 4 and I sent to you my servants the prophets, sending them early; (but you didn't listen or pay attention with your ears;) saying, 
\v 5 Turn every one from his evil way, and from your evil practices, and you will dwell in the land which I gave to you and your fathers, of old and forever. 
\v 6 Don't go after foreign gods, to serve them, and to worship them, that you not provoke me by the works of your hands, to do you hurt. 
\v 7 But you didn't listen to me. 
\p
\v 8 Therefore thus says the Lord; Since you didn't believe my words, 
\v 9 behold, I \add will\add* send and take a family from the north, and will bring them against this land, and against the inhabitants of it, and against all the nations round about it, and I will make them completely waste, and make them a desolation, and a hissing, and an everlasting reproach. 
\v 10 I will destroy from \add among\add* them the voice of joy, and the voice of gladness, the voice of the bridegroom, and the voice of the bride, the scent of ointment, and the light of a candle. 
\v 11 All the land will be a desolation; and they will serve among the nations seventy years. 
\p
\v 12 When the seventy years are fulfilled, I will take vengeance on that nation, and will make them a perpetual desolation. 
\v 13 I will bring upon that land all my words which I have spoken against it, \add even\add* all things that are written in this book. 
\d
\v 14 \sc The Prophecies of Jeremiah against the Nations of Ælam.\sc* 
\p
\v 15 Thus says the Lord, The bow of Ælam is broken, \add even\add* the chief of their power. 
\v 16 I will bring upon Ælam the four winds from the four corners of heaven, and I will disperse them toward all these winds; and there will be no nation \add to\add* which they will not come—\add even\add* the outcasts of Ælam. 
\v 17 I will put them in fear before their enemies who seek their life; and I will bring evils upon them according to my great anger; and I will send forth my sword after them, until I have completely destroyed them. 
\v 18 I will set my throne in Ælam, and will send forth from there king and rulers. 
\v 19 But it will come to pass at the end of days, that I will turn the captivity of Ælam, says the Lord. 
\p
\v 20 In the beginning of the reign of king Zedekiah, there came this word concerning Ælam. 
\c 26 
\p
\v 2 \sc For Egypt, against the Power of Pharaoh Nechao King of Egypt,\sc* who was by the river Euphrates in Charmis, whom Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon struck in the fourth year of Joakim king of Judah. 
\p
\v 3 Take up arms and spears, and draw near to battle; 
\v 4 and harness the horses: mount, you horsemen, and stand ready in your helmets; advance the spears, and put on your breast-plates. 
\p
\v 5 Why do they fear, and turn back? Even because their mighty men will be killed: they have completely fled, and being hemmed in they have not rallied, says the Lord. 
\v 6 Don't let the swift flee, and don't let the mighty man escape to the north: the \add forces\add* at Euphrates have become feeble, and they have fallen. 
\p
\v 7 Who is this \add that\add* will come up as a river, and as rivers roll \add their\add* waves? 
\v 8 The waters of Egypt will come up like a river: and he said, I will go up, and will cover the earth, and will destroy the dwellers in it. 
\v 9 Mount the horses, prepare the chariots; go forth, you warriors of the Ethiopians, and Libyans armed with shields; and mount, you Lydians, bend the bow. 
\v 10 That day \add will be\add* to the Lord our God a day of vengeance, to take vengeance on his enemies: and the sword of the Lord will devour, and be glutted, and be drunk with their blood: for the Lord \add has\add* a sacrifice from the land of the north at the river Euphrates. 
\p
\v 11 Go up to Gilead, and take balm for the virgin daughter of Egypt: in vain have you multiplied your medicines; there is no help for you. 
\v 12 The nations have heard your voice, and the land has been filled with your cry: for the warriors have fainted fighting one against another, \add and\add* both are fallen together. 
\p
\v 13 \sc The Words which the Lord spoke\sc* by Jeremiah, concerning the coming of the king of Babylon to strike the land of Egypt. 
\p
\v 14 Proclaim \add it\add* at Magdol, and declare \add it\add* at Memphis: say, Stand up, and prepare; for the sword has devoured your yew-tree. 
\p
\v 15 Why has \f + \fr 26:15 (46:15) \ft Apis: the sacred Egyptian bull.\f*Apis fled from you? Your choice calf has not remained; for the Lord has completely weakened him. 
\v 16 Your multitude has fainted and fallen; and each one said to his neighbour, Let us arise, and return into our country to our people, from the Grecian sword. 
\v 17 Call the name of Pharaoh Nechao king of Egypt, \f + \fr 26:17 (46:17) \fqa Gr. \ft Σαων εσβι εμωηδ. These are not normal Greek words but a transliteration (or corruption) of a Hebrew phrase corresponding to something like: “a mere noise—his time has passed”\f*Saon-esbi-emoed. 
\v 18 \add As\add* I live, says the Lord God, he will come as Itabyrion among the mountains, and as Carmel that is on the sea. 
\v 19 O daughter of Egypt dwelling \add at home\add*, prepare you stuff for removing: for Memphis will be completely desolate, and will be called Woe, because there are no inhabitants in it. 
\p
\v 20 Egypt is a fair heifer, \add but\add* destruction from the north has come upon her. 
\v 21 Also her hired \add soldiers\add* among her are as fatted calves fed in her; for they also have turned, and fled with one accord: they didn't stand, for the day of destruction was come upon them, and the time of their retribution. 
\v 22 Their voice is as \add that\add* of a hissing snake, for they go upon the sand; they will come upon Egypt with axes, as men who cut wood. 
\v 23 They will cut down her forest, says the Lord, for \add their number\add* cannot at all be conjectured, for it exceeds the locust in multitude, and they are innumerable. 
\v 24 The daughter of Egypt is greatly agitated; she is delivered into the hands of a people from the north. 
\p
\v 25 Behold, I \add will\add* avenge Ammon her son upon Pharaoh, and upon those who trust in him. 
\p
\v 27 But don't be afraid, my servant Jacob, neither be alarmed, Israel: for, behold, I will save you from afar, and your seed from their captivity; and Jacob will return, and be at ease, and sleep, and there will be no one to trouble him. 
\v 28 Don't be afraid, my servant Jacob, says the Lord; for I am with you: she \add who was\add* without fear and in luxury, has been delivered up: for I will make a full end of every nation among whom I have thrust you forth; but I will not cause you to fail: yet will I chastise you in the way of judgment, and will not hold you entirely guiltless. 
\c 27 
\d
\v 1 \sc The Word of the Lord which He spoke against Babylon.\sc* 
\p
\v 2 Proclaim among the nations, and cause the tidings to be heard, and suppress \add them\add* not: say, Babylon is taken, Belus is greatly agitated; the fearless, the luxurious Mærodach is delivered up. 
\v 3 For a nation has come up against her from the north, he will completely ravage her land, and there will be none to dwell in it, neither man nor beast. 
\p
\v 4 In those days, and at that time, the children of Israel will come, they and the children of Judah together; they will proceed, weeping as they go, seeking the Lord their God. 
\v 5 They will ask the way to Zion, for there they will set their faces; and they will come and flee for refuge to the Lord their God; for the everlasting covenant will not be forgotten. 
\p
\v 6 My people have been lost sheep: their shepherds thrust them out, they caused them to wander on the mountains: they went from mountain to hill, they forgot their resting-place. 
\v 7 All who found them consumed them: their enemies said, Don't let us leave them alone, because they have sinned against the Lord: he who gathered their fathers \add had\add* a pasture of righteousness. 
\p
\v 8 Flee out of the midst of Babylon, and from the land of the Chaldeans, and go forth, and be like \f + \fr 27:8 (50:8) \fqa Gr. \ft δράκοντες, serpents or wild beasts\f*leaders going before the flock.
\v 9 For, behold, I stir up against Babylon the gatherings of nations out of the land of the north; and they will set themselves in array against her: from there will she be taken, as the dart of an expert warrior will not return empty. 
\v 10 Chaldea will be a spoil: all who spoil her will be satisfied. 
\p
\v 11 Because you rejoiced, and boasted, \add while\add* plundering my heritage; because you exulted as calves in the grass, and pushed with the horn as bulls. 
\v 12 Your mother is greatly ashamed; your mother who bore you for prosperity is greatly agitated: \add she is\add* the last of the nations, desolate, 
\v 13 because of the Lord's anger: it will not be inhabited, but it will be all a desolation; and every one who passes through Babylon will scowl, and they will hiss at all her plague. 
\p
\v 14 Set yourselves in array against Babylon round about, all you who bend the bow; shoot at her, don't spare your arrows, 
\v 15 and prevail against her: her hands are weakened, her bulwarks are fallen, and her wall is broken down: for it is vengeance from God: take vengeance upon her; as she has done, do to her. 
\v 16 Completely destroy seed out of Babylon, \add and\add* him who holds a sickle in time of harvest: for fear of the Grecian sword, they will return every one to his people, and every one will flee to his own land. 
\p
\v 17 Israel is a wandering sheep; the lions have driven him out: the king of Assyria first devoured him, and afterward this king of Babylon \add has gnawed\add* his bones. 
\v 18 Therefore thus says the Lord; Behold, I \add will\add* take vengeance on the king of Babylon, and upon his land, as I took vengeance on the king of Assyria. 
\v 19 I will restore Israel to his pasture, and he will feed on Carmel and on mount Ephraim and in Gilead, and his soul will be satisfied. 
\v 20 In those days, and at that time, they will seek for the wickedness of Israel, and there will be none; and for the sins of Judah, and they will not be found: for I will be merciful to those who are left 
\v 21 on the land, says the Lord. 
\p Go up against it roughly, and against those who dwell on it: avenge, O sword, and utterly destroy, says the Lord, and do according to all that I command you. 
\v 22 A sound of war, and great destruction in the land of the Chaldeans! 
\v 23 How is the hammer of the whole earth broken and crushed! How is Babylon become a desolation among the nations! 
\v 24 They will come upon you, and you will not know it, Babylon, that you will even be taken captive: you are found and taken, because you resisted the Lord. 
\p
\v 25 The Lord has opened his treasury, and brought forth the weapons of his anger: for the Lord God \add has\add* a work in the land of the Chaldeans. 
\v 26 For her times have come: open her storehouses: search her as a cave, and completely destroy her: let there be no remnant of her. 
\v 27 Dry you up all her fruits, and let them go down to the slaughter: woe to them! For their day has come, and the time of their retribution. 
\v 28 A voice of men fleeing and escaping from the land of Babylon, to declare to Zion the vengeance \add that comes\add* from the Lord our God. 
\p
\v 29 Summon many against Babylon, \add even\add* every one who bends the bow: camp against her all around; let no one of her \add people\add* escape: give to her according to her works; according to all that she has done, do to her: for she has resisted the Lord, the Holy God of Israel. 
\v 30 Therefore her young men will fall in the streets, and all her warriors will be cast down, says the Lord. 
\p
\v 31 Behold, I am against you, haughty one, says the Lord: for your day has come, and the time of your retribution. 
\v 32 Your pride will fail, and fall, and there will be no one to set it up again: and I will kindle a fire in her forest, and it will devour all things around her. 
\p
\v 33 Thus says the Lord; The children of Israel and the children of Judah have been oppressed: all those who have taken them captive have oppressed them together; for they would not let them go. 
\v 34 But their Redeemer is strong; the Lord Almighty is his name: he will enter into judgment with his adversaries, that he may destroy the earth; 
\v 35 and he will sharpen a sword against the Chaldeans, and against the inhabitants of Babylon, and upon her nobles and upon her wise men; 
\v 36 a sword upon her warriors, and they will be weakened: a sword upon their horses, and upon their chariots: 
\v 37 a sword upon their warriors, and upon the mixed people among her; and they will be as women: a sword upon the treasures, and they will be scattered upon her water, 
\v 38 and they will be ashamed: for it is a land of graven \add images\add*; and in the islands, where they boasted. 
\v 39 Therefore idols will dwell in the islands, and the young of monsters will dwell in it: it will not be inhabited any more forever. 
\v 40 As God overthrew Sodom and Gomorrah, and the cities bordering upon them, says the Lord: no man will dwell there, and no son of man will sojourn there. 
\p
\v 41 Behold, a people comes from the north, and a great nation, and many kings will be stirred up from the end of the earth; holding bow and dagger: 
\v 42 \add the people\add* is fierce, and will have no mercy: their voices will sound as the sea, they will ride upon horses, prepared for war, like fire, against you, O daughter of Babylon. 
\v 43 The king of Babylon heard the sound of them, and his hands were enfeebled: anguish overcame him, pangs as of a woman in labor. 
\v 44 Behold, he will come up like a lion from Jordan to Gæthan; for I will speedily drive them from her, and I will set all the youths against her: for who is like me? And who will resist me? And who is this shepherd who will stand before me? 
\p
\v 45 Therefore hear the counsel of the Lord, which he has taken against Babylon; and his plans, which he has planned against the Chaldeans inhabiting \add it\add*: surely lambs of their flock will be destroyed: surely pasture will be cut off from them. 
\v 46 For at the sound of the taking of Babylon the earth will quake, and a cry will be heard among the nations. 
\c 28 
\p
\v 1 Thus says the Lord; Behold, I stir up against Babylon, and against the Chaldeans dwelling therein, a deadly burning wind. 
\v 2 I will send forth against Babylon ravagers, and they will ravage her, and will lay waste her land. Woe to Babylon on every side in the day of her affliction. 
\v 3 Let the archer bend his bow, and him that has armour put it on: and spare not her young men, but destroy all her host. 
\v 4 The wounded will fall in the land of the Chaldeans, and those pierced through will lie outside it. 
\p
\v 5 For Israel and Judah have not been forsaken by their God, by the Lord Almighty; for their land was filled with injustice because of what is holy to Israel. 
\v 6 Flee out of the midst of Babylon, and let each save his own life: and don't be swept away in her wickedness; for it is the time of her judgement from the Lord; he is repaying her in full.
\v 7 Babylon has been a golden cup in the Lord's hand, causing all the earth to be drunk: the nations have drunk of her wine; therefore they were shaken. 
\v 8 Babylon has fallen suddenly, and has broken to pieces: lament for her; take balm for her deadly wound, if by any means she may be healed. 
\v 9 We tried to heal Babylon, but she was not healed: let us forsake her, and every one depart to his own country: for her judgment has reached to the heaven, it has mounted up to the stars. 
\v 10 The Lord has brought forth his judgment: come, and let us declare in Zion the works of the Lord our God. 
\p
\v 11 Prepare the arrows; fill the quivers: the Lord has stirred up the spirit of the king of the Medes: for his wrath is against Babylon, to destroy it completely; for it is the Lord's vengeance, it is the vengeance of his people. 
\v 12 Lift up a standard on the walls of Babylon, prepare the quivers, rouse the guards, prepare the weapons: for the Lord has taken \add the work\add* in hand, and will execute what he has spoken against the inhabitants of Babylon, 
\v 13 dwelling on many waters, and amidst the abundance of her treasures; your end has come truly, to your very core. 
\v 14 For the Lord has sworn by his arm, \add saying\add*, I will fill you with men as with locusts; and those who come down will cry against you.
\p
\q1
\v 15 The Lord made the earth by his power,
\q2 preparing the world by his wisdom,
\q2 by his understanding he stretched out the heaven.
\q1
\v 16 At \add his\add* voice he makes a sound of water in the heaven,
\q2 and brings up clouds from the extremity of the earth;
\q2 he makes lightnings for rain,
\q3 and brings light out of his treasures.
\q1
\v 17 Every man has completely lost understanding;
\q2 every goldsmith is greatly agitated because of his graven \add images\add*:
\q2 for they have cast false \add gods\add*,
\q3 there is no breath in them.
\q1
\v 18 They are vain works,
\q2 objects of scorn;
\q2 in the time of their visitation they will perish.
\q1
\v 19 Not such is Jacob's portion;
\q2 for he who formed all things,
\q2 he is his inheritance;
\q3 the Lord is his name. 
\p
\q1
\v 20 You scatter for me the weapons of war:
\q2 and I will scatter nations by you,
\q2 and will destroy kings by means of you.
\q1
\v 21 By you I will scatter the horse and his rider;
\q2 and by you I will scatter chariots and those who ride in them.
\q1
\v 22 By you I will scatter youth and maiden;
\q2 and by you I will scatter man and woman.
\q1
\v 23 By you I will scatter the shepherd and his flock;
\q2 and by you I will scatter the farmer and his field;
\q2 and by you I will scatter leaders and the captains.
\v 24 I will recompense to Babylon and to all the Chaldeans who dwell \add there\add* all the wrongs that they have done to Zion before your eyes, says the Lord. 
\p
\v 25 Behold, I am against you, the ruined mountain, that destroys the whole earth; and I will stretch out my hand upon you, and will roll you down upon the rocks, and will make you as a burnt mountain. 
\v 26 They will not take from you a stone for a corner, nor a stone for a foundation: for you will be a desolation forever, says the Lord. 
\p
\v 27 Lift up a standard in the land, sound the trumpet among the nations, consecrate the nations against her, summon against her the kingdoms of Ararat at my command, and  the people of Achanaz; set up archers against her; bring up horses against her like a swarm of locusts. 
\v 28 Bring up nations against her, \add even\add* the king of the Medes and of the whole earth, his rulers, and all his captains. 
\v 29 The earth has quaked and been troubled, because the purpose of the Lord has risen up against Babylon, to make the land of Babylon a desolation, and uninhabitable. 
\p
\v 30 The warrior of Babylon has failed to fight; they will sit there in the siege; their power is broken; they have become like women; her tents have been set on fire; her bars are broken. 
\v 31 One will rush, running to meet \add another\add* runner, and one \add will go\add* with tidings to meet \add another\add* with tidings, to bring tidings to the king of Babylon, that his city is taken. 
\v 32 From the farthest crossings they were taken, and their strongholds have been burnt with fire, and his warriors are going out. 
\p
\v 33 For thus says the Lord, The houses of the king of Babylon are like a ripe threshing floor; they will  be threshed; yet a little while, and her harvest will come. 
\p
\v 34 He has devoured me, he has torn me asunder, airy darkness has come upon me; Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon has swallowed me up, like a ravenous beast he has filled his belly with my delicacies. 
\v 35 Let my troubles and my distresses be upon Babylon, says the inhabitant of Zion; and my blood upon the Chaldeans, says Jerusalem. 
\p
\v 36 Therefore thus says the Lord, Behold, I will judge your adversary, and I will execute vengeance for you; and I will make her sea desolate, and dry up her spring. 
\v 37 Babylon will be a desolation, and will not be inhabited. 
\v 38 For they rose up together as lions, and as lions' whelps. 
\v 39 In their fevered state I will give them a drink, and make them drunk, so they grown drowsy, and sleep an everlasting sleep, and never awake, says the Lord. 
\v 40 Bring them down as lambs to the slaughter, and rams together with goats. 
\p
\v 41 How has the boast of all the earth been taken and caught in a snare! How has Babylon become a desolation among the nations! 
\v 42 The sea has come up upon Babylon with the sound of its waves, and she is covered. 
\v 43 Her cities have become like a dry and trackless land; not so much as one \add man\add* will dwell in it, neither will a son of man lodge in it. 
\v 44 I will take vengeance on Babylon, and bring forth out of her mouth what she has swallowed down, and the nations will no more be gathered to her: 
\v 49 and in Babylon the slain of all the earth will fall. 
\v 50 Go forth from the land, you who escape, and don't stay; you who are afar off, remember the Lord, and let Jerusalem come into your mind. 
\v 51 We are ashamed, because we have heard our reproach; disgrace has covered our face; aliens have come into our sanctuary, \add even\add* into the house of the Lord. 
\p
\v 52 Therefore, behold, days are coming, says the Lord, when I will take vengeance upon her graven \add images\add*: and the slain will fall in all her land. 
\v 53 For even if Babylon should rise like the heavens, and though she should strengthen her walls with her power, from me will come those who will destroy her, says the Lord. 
\v 54 A sound of a cry in Babylon, and great destruction in the land of the Chaldeans: 
\v 55 for the Lord has completely destroyed Babylon, and cut off from her the great voice sounding as many waters: he has consigned her voice to destruction. 
\v 56 For distress has come upon Babylon, her warriors are taken, their bows are useless: for God repays them. 
\v 57 The Lord repays, and will make her leaders and her wise men and her captains completely drunk, says the King, the Lord Almighty is his name. 
\p
\v 58 Thus says the Lord, The wall of Babylon was made broad, but it will be completely broken down, and her high gates will be burnt with fire; and the peoples will not labour in vain, nor the nations fail in \add their\add* rule. 
\p
\v 59 \sc The Word which the Lord commanded the Prophet Jeremiah\sc* to say to Saræas son of Nerias, son of Maasæas, when he went from Zedekiah king of Judah to Babylon, in the fourth year of his reign. And Saræas was an officer in charge of gifts.
\v 60 Jeremiah wrote in a book all the evils which should come upon Babylon, \add even\add* all these words that are written against Babylon. 
\v 61 Jeremiah said to Saræas, When you have come to Babylon, and you see and read all these words; 
\v 62 then you will say, O Lord God, you have spoken against this place, to destroy it, and that there should be none to dwell in it, neither man nor beast; for it will be a desolation forever. 
\v 63 It will come to pass, when you cease from reading this book, that you will tie a stone on it, and cast it into the midst of Euphrates; 
\v 64 and will say, Thus will Babylon sink, and not rise, because of the evils which I bring upon it. 
\c 29 
\d
\v 1 \sc Thus says the Lord against the Philistines;\sc* 
\p
\v 2 Behold, waters come up from the north, and will become a sweeping torrent, and it will sweep away the land, and all that fills it; the city, and those who dwell in it: and men will cry and all who dwell in the land will howl, 
\v 3 at the sound of his rushing, at \add the sound of\add* his hoofs, and at the rattling of his chariots, at the noise of his wheels: the fathers didn't turn to their children because of the weakness of their hands, 
\v 4 in the day that is coming to destroy all the Philistines: and I will completely destroy Tyre and Sidon, and all the rest of their allies: for the Lord will destroy the remaining \add inhabitants\add* of the islands. 
\v 5 Baldness has come upon Gaza; Ascalon is cast away, and the remnant of the Enakim. 
\p
\v 6 How long will you strike, O sword of the Lord? How long will it be before you are quiet? Return into your sheath, rest, and be removed. 
\p
\v 7 How can it be quiet, because the Lord has given it a commission against Ascalon, and against the regions on the sea-coast, to awake against the remaining \add lands\add*! 
\c 30 
\p
\v 1 \sc Concerning Idumea,\sc* thus says the Lord; There is no longer wisdom in Thæman, counsel has perished from the wise ones, their wisdom has gone, 
\v 2 their land has been deceived. Dwell deep, you who inhabit Dædam, for he has worked grievously: I brought trouble upon him in the time at which I visited him. 
\v 3 For grape-gatherers have come, who will not leave you a remnant; as thieves by night, they will lay their hand upon \add your possessions\add*. 
\p
\v 4 For I have stripped Esau, I have uncovered their secret places; they will have no power to hide themselves, they have perished \add each\add* by the hand of his brother and his neighbour, and he is no more.
\v 5 Leave your orphans that they may live, and I will preserve them, and let your widows trust in me. 
\p
\v 6 For thus says the Lord; They who were not appointed to drink the cup have drunk \add it\add*; and you will by no means be cleared: 
\v 7 for by myself I have sworn, says the Lord, that you will be a desolation, and a reproach, and a curse; and all her cities will be desolate forever. 
\p
\v 8 I have heard a report from the Lord, and he has sent messengers to the nations, \add saying\add*, Assemble yourselves, and come against her; rise up to war. 
\v 9 I have made you small among the nations, completely contemptible among men. 
\v 10 Your insolence has risen up against you, the fierceness of your heart has burst the holes of the rocks, it has seized upon the strength of a lofty hill; for as an eagle he set his nest on high: from there will I bring you down. 
\p
\v 11 Idumea will be a desert: every one who passes by will hiss at it. 
\v 12 As Sodom was overthrown and Gomorrah and their inhabitants, says the Lord Almighty, no man will dwell there, nor will any son of man inhabit there. 
\v 13 Behold, he will come up like a lion out of the midst of Jordan to the place of Ætham: for I will speedily drive them from it; set the young men against her: for who is like me? And who will withstand me? And who \add is\add* this shepherd, who will confront me? 
\p
\v 14 Therefore hear the counsel of the Lord, which he has framed against Idumea; and his device, which he has devised against the inhabitants of Thæman: surely the least of the sheep will be swept off; surely their dwelling will be made desolate for them. 
\v 15 For at the sound of their fall the earth was scared, and the cry of the sea was not heard. 
\v 16 Behold, he will look \add upon her\add* as an eagle, and spread forth \add his\add* wings over her strongholds; and the heart of the mighty men of Idumea will be in that day as the heart of a woman in her labour-pains. 
\p
\v 17 \sc Concerning the sons of Ammon\sc* thus says the Lord, Are there no sons in Israel? Or have they no one to succeed \add them\add*? Why has Melchol inherited Gilead, and why will their people dwell in their cities? 
\v 18 Therefore, behold, days are coming, says the Lord, when I will cause a tumult of wars to be heard in Rabbath; and they will become a waste and ruined place, and her altars will be burned with fire; then Israel will succeed to his dominion. 
\v 19 Howl, O Esebon, for Gai has perished; cry, you daughters of Rabbath, gird yourselves with sackcloth, and lament; for Melchol will go into banishment, his priests and his princes together. 
\p
\v 20 Why do you exult in the plains of the Enakim, you haughty daughter, who trust in \add your\add* treasures, who say, Who will come in to me? 
\v 21 Behold, I \add will\add* bring terror upon you, says the Lord, from all the country round about you; and you will be scattered every one right before him, and there is no one to gather you. 
\p
\v 23 \sc Concerning Kedar the Queen of the Palace, whom Nebuchadnezzar King of Babylon struck,\sc* thus says the Lord; 
\p Arise, and go up to Kedar, and fill the sons of Kedem. 
\v 24 They will take their tents and their sheep, they will take for themselves their garments, and all their baggage and their camels; summon destruction against them from every side. 
\v 25 Flee, dig very deep for a dwelling-place, you who dwell in the palace; for the king of Babylon has framed a counsel, and devised a device against you. 
\p
\v 26 Rise up, and go up against a nation settled \add and\add* dwelling at ease, who have no doors, nor bolts, nor bars, \add who\add* dwell alone. 
\v 27 Their camels will be a spoil, and the multitude of their cattle will be destroyed: and I will scatter them as chaff with every wind, having their hair cut about their foreheads, I will bring on their overthrow from all sides, says the Lord. 
\v 28 The palace will be a resting-place for ostriches, and desolate forever: no man will abide there, and no son of man will dwell there. 
\p
\v 29 \sc Concerning Damascus.\sc* Emath is brought to shame, and Arphath: for they have heard an evil report: they are amazed, they are angry, they will be completely unable to rest. 
\v 30 Damascus is completely weakened, she is put to flight; trembling has seized upon her. 
\v 31 How has my city not been forsaken? They loved a village.
\p
\v 32 Therefore the young men will fall in your streets, and all your warriors will fall, says the Lord. 
\v 33 I will kindle a fire in the wall of Damascus, and it will devour the streets of the son of Ader. 
\c 31 
\p
\v 1 Thus has the Lord said concerning \sc Moab\sc*, Woe to Nabau! For it has perished: Cariathaim is taken: Amath and Agath are put to shame. 
\v 2 There is no longer any healing for Moab, \add nor\add* glorying in Esebon: he has devised evils against her: we have cut her off from \add being\add* a nation, and she will be completely still: after you will go a sword; 
\v 3 for \add there is\add* a voice of \add men\add* crying out of Oronaim, destruction and great ruin. 
\v 4 Moab is ruined, proclaim \add it\add* to Zogora: 
\v 5 for Aloth is filled with weeping: one will go up weeping by the way of Oronaim; you have heard a cry of destruction. 
\p
\v 6 Flee, and save your lives, and you will be as a wild ass in the desert. 
\v 7 Since you have trusted in your strong-hold, therefore you will be taken: and Chamos will go forth into captivity, and his priests, and his princes together. 
\v 8 Destruction will come upon every city, it will surely not escape; the valley also will perish, and the plain country will be completely destroyed, as the Lord has said. 
\v 9 Set marks upon Moab, for she will be touched with a plague-spot, and all her cities will become desolate; where \add will there be\add* an inhabitant for her? 
\v 10 Cursed is the man who does the works of the Lord carelessly, keeping back his sword from blood. 
\p
\v 11 Moab has been at ease from a child, and trusted in his glory; he has not poured out \add his liquor\add* from vessel to vessel, and has not gone into banishment, therefore his taste remained in him, and his smell didn't depart. 
\v 12 Therefore, behold, his days are coming, says the Lord, when I will send upon him bad leaders, and they will lead him astray, and they will completely break in pieces his possessions, and will cut his horns apart. 
\v 13 Moab will be ashamed of Chamos, as the house of Israel was ashamed of Bethel their hope, having trusted in them. 
\p
\v 14 How will you say, We are strong, and men strong for war? 
\v 15 Moab is ruined, \add even\add* his city, and his choice young men have gone down to slaughter. 
\v 16 The day of Moab is near at hand, and his wickedness moves swiftly \add to vengeance\add*. 
\v 17 Shake \add the head\add* at him, all you who are round about him; all \add of you\add* utter his name; say, How is the glorious staff broken to pieces, the rod of magnificence! 
\p
\v 18 Come down from \add your\add* glory, and sit down in a damp place: Dæbon will be broken, because Moab is destroyed: there has gone up against you one to ravage your strong-hold. 
\v 19 Stand by the way, and look, you who dwell in Arer; and ask him who is fleeing, and him who escapes, and say, What has happened? 
\p
\v 20 Moab is put to shame, because he is broken: howl and cry; proclaim in Arnon, that Moab has perished. 
\v 21 Judgment is coming against the land of Misor, upon Chelon, and Rephas, and Mophas, 
\v 22 and upon Dæbon, and upon Nabau, and upon the house of Dæthlathaim, 
\v 23 and upon Cariathaim, and upon the house of Gæmol, and upon the house of Maon, 
\v 24 and upon Carioth, and upon Bosor, and upon all the cities of Moab, far and near. 
\v 25 The horn of Moab is broken, and his arm is crushed. 
\p
\v 26 Make him drunk; for he has magnified himself against the Lord: and Moab will clap with his hand, and will be himself a laughing-stock also. 
\v 27 For surely Israel was to you a laughing-stock, and was found among your thefts, because you fought against him. 
\v 28 The inhabitants of Moab have left the cities, and dwelt in rocks; they have become as doves nestling in rocks, at the mouth of a cave. 
\p
\v 29 I have heard of the pride of Moab, he has greatly heightened his pride and his haughtiness, and his heart has been lifted up. 
\v 30 But I know his works: is it not enough for him? Has he not done thus? 
\p
\v 31 Therefore howl for Moab on all sides; cry out against the shorn men \add in\add* a gloomy place. I will weep for you, 
\v 32 O vine of Aserema, as with the weeping of Jazer: your branches have gone over the sea, they reached the cities of Jazer: destruction has come upon your fruits, \add and\add* upon your grape-gatherers. 
\v 33 Joy and gladness have been completely swept off the land of Moab: and \add though\add* there was wine in your presses, in the morning they didn't tread it, nor in the evening did they raise the cry of joy. 
\v 34 From the cry of Esebon even to Ætam their cities uttered their voice, from Zogor to Oronaim, and their tidings \add as\add* a heifer of three years old, for the water also of Nebrin will be dried up. 
\p
\v 35 I will destroy Moab, says the Lord, as he comes up to the altar, and burns incense to his gods. 
\v 36 Therefore the heart of Moab will sound as pipes, my heart will sound as a pipe for the shorn men; because what \add every\add* man has gained has perished from him. 
\v 37 They will all have their heads shaved in every place, and every beard will be shaved; and all hands will beat \add the breasts\add*, and on all loins will be sackcloth. 
\v 38 On all the housetops of Moab, and in his streets \add will be mourning\add*: for I have broken \add him\add*, says the Lord, as a vessel, which is useless. 
\v 39 How has he changed! How has Moab turned \add his\add* back! Moab is put to shame, and become a laughing-stock, and an object of anger to all who are round about him. 
\p
\v 40 For thus said the Lord; 
\v 41 Carioth is taken, and the strong-holds have been taken together. 
\v 42 Moab will perish from being a multitude, because he has magnified himself against the Lord. 
\v 43 A snare, and fear, and the pit, are upon you, O inhabitant of Moab. 
\v 44 He who flees from the terror will fall into the pit, and he who comes up out of the pit will even be taken in the snare: for I will bring these things upon Moab in the year of their visitation. 
\c 32 
\p
\v 15 Thus said the Lord God of Israel; Take the cup of this unmixed wine from my hand, and you will cause all the nations to drink, to whom I send you. 
\v 16 They will drink, and vomit, and be mad, because of the sword which I send among them. 
\p
\v 17 So I took the cup out of the Lord's hand, and caused the nations to whom the Lord sent me to drink: 
\v 18 Jerusalem, and the cities of Judah, and the kings of Judah, and his princes, to make them a desert place, a desolation, and a hissing; 
\v 19 and Pharaoh king of Egypt, and his servants, and his nobles, and all his people; 
\v 20 and all the mingled \add people\add*, and all the kings of the Philistines, and Ascalon, and Gaza, and Accaron, and the remnant of Azotus, 
\v 21 and Idumea, and the land of Moab, and the children of Ammon, 
\v 22 and the kings of Tyre, and the kings of Sidon, and the kings in the \add country\add* beyond the sea, 
\v 23 and Dædan, and Thæman, and Ros, and every one who is shaved around the face, 
\v 24 and all the mingled \add people\add* lodging in the wilderness, 
\v 25 and all the kings of Ælam, and all the kings of the Persians, 
\v 26 and all the kings from the north, the far and the near, each one with his brother, and all the kingdoms which are on the face of the earth. 
\p
\v 27 You will say to them, Thus said the Lord Almighty; Drink, be drunk; and you will vomit, and fall, and will not rise, because of the sword which I send among you. 
\v 28 It will come to pass, when they refuse to take the cup out of your hand, to drink it, that you will say, Thus said the Lord; You will surely drink. 
\v 29 For I am beginning to afflict the city whereon my name is called, and you will by no means be held guiltless: for I am calling a sword upon all who dwell upon the earth. 
\p
\v 30 You will prophesy against them these words, and will say, The Lord will speak from on high, from his sanctuary he will utter his voice; he will pronounce a declaration on his place; and these will answer like men gathering grapes: and destruction is coming on those who dwell on the earth, 
\v 31 \add even\add* upon \add the extreme\add* part of the earth; for the Lord \add has\add* a controversy with the nations, he is pleading with all flesh, and the ungodly are given to the sword, says the Lord. 
\p
\v 32 Thus said the Lord; Behold, evils are proceeding from nation to nation, and a great whirlwind goes forth from the end of the earth. 
\v 33 The killed of the Lord will be in the day of the Lord from \add one\add* end of the earth even to the \add other\add* end of the earth: they will not be buried; they will be as dung on the face of the earth. 
\v 34 Howl, you shepherds, and cry; and lament, you rams of the flock: for your days have been completed for slaughter, and you will fall as the choice rams. 
\v 35 Flight will perish from the shepherds, and safety from the rams of the flock. 
\v 36 A voice of the crying of the shepherds, and a moaning of the sheep and the rams: for the Lord has destroyed their pastures. 
\v 37 The peaceable abodes that remain will be destroyed before the fierceness of my anger. 
\v 38 He has forsaken his lair, like a lion: for their land has become desolate before the great sword. 
\c 33 
\p
\v 1 \sc In the beginning of the Reign of King Joakim Son of Josiah there came this Word from the Lord.\sc* 
\p
\v 2 Thus said the Lord; Stand in the court of the Lord's house, and you will declare to all the Jews, and to all who come to worship in the house of the Lord, all the words which I commanded you to speak to them; don't leave out a single word. 
\v 3 Perhaps they will hear, and turn every one from his evil way: then I will cease from the evils which I purpose to do to them, because of their evil practices. 
\v 4 You will say, Thus said the Lord; If you will not listen to me, to walk in my statutes which I set before you, 
\v 5 to listen to the words of my servants the prophets, whom I send to you early in the morning; yes, I sent them, but you didn't listen to me; 
\v 6 then I will make this house like Shiloh, and I will make \add this\add* city a curse to all the nations of all the earth. 
\p
\v 7 The priests, and the false prophets, and all the people heard Jeremiah speaking these words in the house of the Lord. 
\v 8 It happened, when Jeremiah had ceased speaking all that the Lord had ordered him to speak to all the people, that the priests and the false prophets and all the people took him, saying, 
\v 9 You will surely die, because you have prophesied in the name of the Lord, saying, This house will be like Shiloh, and this city will be made quite destitute of inhabitants. 
\p And all the people assembled against Jeremiah in the house of the Lord. 
\v 10 The princes of Judah heard this word, and they went up out of the house of the king to the house of the Lord, and sat in the entrance of the new gate. 
\v 11 Then the priests and the false prophets said to the princes and to all the people, The judgment of death \add is due\add* to this man; because he has prophesied against this city, as you have heard with your ears. 
\p
\v 12 Then Jeremiah spoke to the princes, and to all the people, saying, The Lord sent me to prophesy against this house and against this city, all the words which you have heard. 
\v 13 Now amend your ways and your works, and listen to the voice of the Lord; and the Lord will cease from the evils which he has pronounced against you. 
\v 14 Behold, I am in your hands; do to me as is expedient, and as it is best for you. 
\v 15 But know for a certainty, that if you kill me, you bring innocent blood upon yourselves, and upon this city, and upon those who dwell in it; for in truth the Lord has sent me to you to speak in your ears all these words. 
\p
\v 16 Then the princes and all the people said to the priests and to the false prophets; Judgment of death isn't \add due\add* to this man; for he has spoken to us in the name of the Lord our God. 
\v 17 There rose up men of the elders of the land, and said to all the assembly of the people, 
\v 18 Micah the Morathite lived in the days of Hezekiah king of Judah, and said to all the people of Judah, Thus says the Lord; Zion will be ploughed as a field, and Jerusalem will become a desolation, and the mountain of the house will be a thicket of trees. 
\v 19 Did Hezekiah and all Judah in any way kill him? Was it not that they feared the Lord, and they made supplication before the Lord, and the Lord ceased from the evils which he \add had\add* pronounced against them? Because we have worked great evil against our own souls. 
\p
\v 20 There was \add another\add* man prophesying in the name of the Lord, Urias the son of Samæas of Cariathiarim; and he prophesied concerning this land according to all the words of Jeremiah. 
\v 21 King Joakim and all the princes heard all his words, and sought to kill him; and Urias heard \add it\add* and went into Egypt. 
\v 22 The king sent men into Egypt; 
\v 23 and they brought him from there, and brought him in to the king; and he struck him with the sword, and cast him into the sepulchre of the children of his people. 
\v 24 Nevertheless the hand of Achicam son of Saphan was with Jeremiah, to prevent his being delivered into the hands of the people, or being killed. 
\c 34 
\p
\v 2 Thus said the Lord; Make to yourself bonds and yokes, and put \add them\add* about your neck, 
\v 3 and you will send them to the king of Idumea, and to the king of Moab, and to the king of the children of Ammon, and to the king of Tyre, and to the king of Sidon, by the hands of their messengers who come to meet them at Jerusalem to Zedekiah king of Judah. 
\v 4 You will commission them to say to their lords, Thus said the Lord God of Israel; Thus will you say to your lords; 
\v 5 I have made the earth by my great power, and with my high arm, and I will give it to whoever it will seem \add good\add* in my eyes. 
\v 6 I gave the earth to Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon to serve him, and the wild beasts of the field to labour for him. 
\v 8 The nation and kingdom, all who will not put their neck under the yoke of the king of Babylon, I will visit them with sword and famine, says the Lord, until they are consumed by his hand. 
\p
\v 9 Don't you listen to your false prophets, nor to those who divine to you, nor to those who foretell events by dreams to you, nor to your auguries, nor your sorcerers, who say, You will by no means work for the king of Babylon: 
\v 10 for they prophesy lies to you, to remove you far from your land. 
\v 11 But the nation which will put its neck under the yoke of the king of Babylon, and serve him, I will even leave it upon its land, and it will serve him, and dwell in it. 
\p
\v 12 I spoke also to Zedekiah king of Judah according to all these words, saying, Put your neck into \add the yoke\add*, 
\v 14 and serve the king of Babylon. For they prophesy unrighteous \add words\add* to you, 
\v 15 for I didn't send them, says the Lord; and they prophesy \add in\add* my name unjustly, that I might destroy you, and you should perish, and your prophets, who unrighteously prophesy lies to you. 
\p
\v 16 I spoke to you, and to all this people, and to the priests, saying, Thus said the Lord; Don't listen to the words of the prophets who prophesy to you, saying, Behold, the vessels of the Lord's house will return from Babylon: for they prophesy to you unrighteous \add words\add*. I didn't send them. 
\v 18 If they are prophets, and if the word of the Lord is in them, let them meet me, for thus has the Lord said. 
\p
\v 19 As for the remaining vessels, 
\v 20 which the king of Babylon didn't take, when he carried Jechonias prisoner out of Jerusalem, 
\v 22 they will go into Babylon, says the Lord. 
\c 35 
\p
\v 1 It happened in the fourth year of Zedekiah king of Judah, in the fifth month, \add that\add* Ananias the false prophet, the son of Azor, from Gabaon, spoke to me in the house of the Lord, in the sight of the priests and all the people, saying, 
\v 2 Thus says the Lord; I have broken the yoke of the king of Babylon. 
\v 3 Yet two full years, and I will return into this place the vessels of the house of the Lord, 
\v 4 and Jechonias, and the captivity of Judah: for I will break the yoke of the king of Babylon. 
\p
\v 5 Then Jeremiah spoke to Ananias in the sight of all the people, and in the sight of the priests who stood in the house of the Lord, 
\v 6 and Jeremiah said, May the Lord indeed do thus; may he confirm your word which you prophesy, to return the vessels of the house of the Lord, and all the captivity, out of Babylon to this place. 
\v 7 Nevertheless hear the word of the Lord which I speak in your ears, and in the ears of all the people. 
\v 8 The prophets who were before me and before you of old, also prophesied over much country, and against great kingdoms, concerning war. 
\v 9 \add As for\add* the prophet who has prophesied for peace, when the word has come \add to pass\add*, they will know the prophet whom the Lord has sent them in truth. 
\p
\v 10 Then Ananias took the yokes from the neck of Jeremiah in the sight of all the people, and broke them to pieces. 
\v 11 Ananias spoke in the presence of all the people, saying, Thus said the Lord; Thus will I break the yoke of the king of Babylon from the necks of all the nations. And Jeremiah went his way. 
\p
\v 12 The word of the Lord came to Jeremiah, after that Ananias had broken the yokes off his neck, saying, 
\v 13 Go and speak to Ananias, saying, Thus says the Lord; You have broken the yokes of wood; but I will make instead of them yokes of iron. 
\v 14 For thus said the Lord, I have put a yoke of iron on the neck of all the nations, so they may serve the king of Babylon. 
\v 15 Jeremiah said to Ananias, The Lord has not sent you; and you have caused this people to trust in unrighteousness. 
\v 16 Therefore thus said the Lord: Behold, I \add will\add* cast you off from the face of the earth: this year you will die. 
\v 17 So he died in the seventh month. 
\c 36 
\p
\v 1 These are the words of the book which Jeremiah sent from Jerusalem to the elders of the captivity, and to the priests, and to the false prophets, even an epistle to Babylon for the captivity, and to all the people; 
\v 2 (after the departure of Jechonias the king and the queen, and the eunuchs, and every freeman, and bondman, and artificer, out of Jerusalem;) 
\v 3 by the hand of Eleasan son of Saphan, and Gamarias son of Chelcias, (whom Zedekiah king of Judah sent to the king of Babylon to Babylon) saying, 
\p
\v 4 Thus said the Lord God of Israel concerning the captivity which I caused to be carried away from Jerusalem; 
\v 5 Build houses, and inhabit \add them\add*; and plant gardens, and eat its fruits; 
\v 6 and take wives, and father sons and daughters; and take wives for your sons, and give your daughters to husbands, and be multiplied, and don't be diminished. 
\v 7 Seek the peace of the land into which I have carried you captive, and you will pray to the Lord for the people: for in its peace you will \add have\add* peace. 
\p
\v 8 For thus says the Lord; Don't let the false prophets who are among you persuade you, and don't let your diviners persuade you, and don't listen to your dreams which you dream. 
\v 9 For they prophesy to you unrighteous \add words\add* in my name; and I didn't send them. 
\v 10 For thus said the Lord; When seventy years will be on the point of being accomplished at Babylon, I will visit you, and will confirm my words to you, to bring back your people to this place. 
\v 11 I will devise for you a device of peace, and not evil, to bestow upon you these \add good things\add*. 
\v 12 Pray to me, and I will listen to you: and earnestly seek me, and you will find me; 
\v 13 for you will seek me with your whole heart. 
\v 14 I will appear to you: 
\v 15 because you said, The Lord has appointed for us prophets in Babylon: 
\p
\v 21 Thus says the Lord concerning Achiab, and concerning Zedekiah; Behold, I \add will\add* deliver them into the hands of the king of Babylon; and he will strike them in your sight. 
\v 22 They will make of them a curse in all the captivity of Judah in Babylon, saying, The Lord do to you as he did to Zedekiah, and as he did to Achiab, whom the king of Babylon fried in the fire; 
\v 23 because of the wickedness which they worked in Israel, and \add because\add* they committed adultery with the wives of their fellow-citizens, and spoke a word in my name, which I did not command them \add to speak\add*, and I am witness, says the Lord. 
\p
\v 24 To Samæas the Ælamite you will say, 
\v 25 I didn't send you in my name: and to Zephaniah the priest the son of Maasæas say, 
\v 26 The Lord has made you priest in the place of Jodae the priest, to be ruler in the house of the Lord over every prophet, and to every madman, and you will put them in prison, and into the dungeon. 
\v 27 Now why have you reviled together Jeremiah of Anathoth, who prophesied to you? 
\v 28 Did he not send for this purpose? For in the course of this month he sent to you to Babylon, saying, It is far off: build houses, and inhabit \add them\add*; and plant gardens, and eat their fruit. 
\v 29 Zephaniah read the book in the ears of Jeremiah. 
\p
\v 30 Then the word of the Lord came to Jeremiah, saying, 
\v 31 Send to the captivity, saying, Thus says the Lord concerning Samæas the Ælamite, Since Samæas has prophesied to you, and I didn't send him, and he has made you to trust in wickedness, 
\v 32 therefore thus says the Lord; Behold, I will visit Samæas, and his family: and there will not be a man of them among you to see the good which I will do to you: they will not see \add it\add*. 
\c 37 
\p
\v 1 \sc The Word that came to Jeremiah from the Lord, saying,\sc* 
\v 2 Thus says the Lord God of Israel, saying, 
\p Write all the words which I have spoken to you in a book. 
\v 3 For, behold, days are coming, says the Lord, when I will bring back the captivity of my people Israel and Judah, said the Lord: and I will bring them back to the land which I gave to their fathers, and they will be lords of it. 
\p
\v 4 \sc And these are the Words which the Lord spoke concerning Israel and Judah:\sc* 
\p
\v 5 Thus said the Lord: You will hear a sound of fear, \add there is\add* fear, and there isn't peace. 
\v 6 Enquire, and see if a male has given birth to a child? And \add ask\add* concerning the fear, in which they will hold their loins, and \add look for\add* safety: for I have seen every man, and his hands are on his loins; \add their\add* faces are turned to paleness. 
\v 7 For that day is great, and there isn't such \add another\add*; and it is a time of \f + \fr 37:7 \fqa Gr. \ft constraint.\f*distress to Jacob; but he will be saved out of it. 
\v 8 In that day, said the Lord, I will break the yoke off their neck, and will burst their bonds, and they will no longer serve strangers: 
\v 9 but they will serve the Lord their God; and I will raise up to them David their king. 
\p
\v 12 Thus says the Lord; I have brought on \add you\add* destruction; your stroke is painful. 
\v 13 There is no one to judge your cause: you have been painfully treated for healing, there is no help for you. 
\v 14 All your friends have forgotten you; they will surely not ask \add about you\add*, for I have struck you with the stroke of an enemy, \add even\add* severe correction: your sins have abounded above all your wickedness. 
\v 16 Therefore all who devour you will be eaten, and all your enemies will eat all their \add own\add* flesh. Your sins have abounded beyond the multitude of your iniquities, \add therefore\add* they have done these things to you. And those who spoil you will become a spoil, and I will give up to be plundered all who have plundered you. 
\v 17 For I will bring about your healing, I will heal you of your grievous wound, says the Lord; for you are called Dispersed: she is your prey, for no one seeks after her. 
\p
\v 18 Thus said the Lord; Behold, I will turn the captivity of Jacob, and will have pity upon his prisoners; and the city will be built upon her hill, and the people will settle after their manner. 
\v 19 There will go forth from them singers, \add even\add* the sound of men making merry: and I will multiply them, and they will surely not be diminished. 
\v 20 Their sons will go in as before, and their testimonies will be established before me, and I will visit those who afflict them. 
\v 21 Their mighty ones will be over them, and their prince will go out from them; and I will gather them, and they will return to me: for who is this who has set his heart to return to me? Says the Lord. 
\p
\v 23 For the wrathful anger of the Lord has gone forth, \add even\add* a whirlwind of anger has gone forth: it will come upon the ungodly. 
\v 24 The fierce anger of the Lord will not return, until he executes \add it\add*, and until he establishes the purpose of his heart: in the latter days you will know these things. 
\c 38 
\p
\v 1 At that time, says the Lord, I will be a God to the family of Israel, and they will be my people. 
\v 2 Thus says the Lord, I found him warm in the wilderness with those who were killed with the sword: go and don't destroy Israel. 
\v 3 The Lord appeared to him from afar, \add saying\add*, I have loved you with an everlasting love: therefore have I drawn you in compassion. 
\v 4 For I will build you, and you will be built, O virgin of Israel: you will yet take your timbrel, and go forth with the party of those who make merry. 
\v 5 For you have planted vineyards on the mountains of Samaria: plant, and praise. 
\v 6 For it is a day when those who plead on the mountains of Ephraim will call, \add saying\add*, Arise, and go up to Zion to the Lord your God. 
\p
\v 7 For thus says the Lord to Jacob; Rejoice, and exult over the head of the nations: make proclamation; praise: say, The Lord has delivered his people, the remnant of Israel. 
\v 8 Behold, I bring them from the north, and will gather them from the end of the earth to the feast of the passover: and \add the people\add* will father a great multitude, and they will return here. 
\v 9 They went out with weeping, and I will bring them back with consolation, causing them to lodge by the channels of waters in a straight way, and they will not err in it: for I have become a father to Israel, and Ephraim is my first-born. 
\p
\v 10 Hear the words of the Lord, you nations, and proclaim \add them\add* to the islands far off; say, He who scattered Israel will also gather him, and keep him as one who feeds his flock. 
\v 11 For the Lord has ransomed Jacob, he has rescued him out of the hand of them \add who were\add* stronger than he. 
\v 12 They will come, and will rejoice in the mount of Zion, and will come to the good things of the Lord, \add even\add* to a land of grain, and wine, and fruits, and cattle, and sheep: and their soul will be as a fruitful tree; and they will hunger no more. 
\v 13 Then will the virgins rejoice in the assembly of youth, and the old men will rejoice; and I will turn their mourning into joy, and will make them merry. 
\v 14 I will expand and cheer with wine the soul of the priests, the sons of Levi, and my people will be satisfied with my good things: thus says the Lord. 
\p
\v 15 A voice was heard in Rama, of lamentation, and of weeping, and wailing; Rachel would not cease weeping for her children, because they are not. 
\p
\v 16 Thus says the Lord; Let your voice cease from weeping, and your eyes from your tears: for there is a reward for your works; and they will return from the land of \add your\add* enemies. 
\v 17 \add There will be\add* an abiding \add home\add* for your children. 
\p
\v 18 I have heard the sound of Ephraim lamenting, \add and saying\add*, You have chastened me, and I was chastened; I as a calf was not \add willingly\add* taught: turn me, and I will turn; for you \add are\add* the Lord my God. 
\v 19 For after my captivity I repented; and after I knew, I groaned for the day of shame, and showed you that I bore reproach from my youth. 
\v 20 Ephraim is a beloved son, a pleasing child to me: for because my words are in him, I will surely remember him: therefore I hurried \add to help\add* him; I will surely have mercy on him, says the Lord. 
\p
\v 21 Prepare yourself, O Zion; execute vengeance; look to your ways: return, O virgin of Israel, by the way by which you went, return mourning to your cities. 
\v 22 How long, O disgraced daughter, will you turn away? For the Lord has created safety for a new plantation: men will go about in safety. 
\p
\v 23 For thus says the Lord; They will yet speak this word in the land of Judah, and in the cities of it, when I will turn his captivity; blessed be the Lord on his righteous holy mountain! 
\v 24 There will be dwellers in the cities of Judah, and in all his land, together with the farmer, and \add the shepherd\add* will go forth with the flock. 
\v 25 For I have saturated every thirsting soul, and filled every hungry soul. 
\v 26 Therefore I awoke, and beheld; and my sleep was sweet to me. 
\p
\v 27 Therefore, behold, days are coming, says the Lord, when I will sow the house of Israel and the house of Judah with the seed of man, and the seed of beast. 
\v 28 It will come to pass, that as I watched over them, to pull down, and to afflict, so will I watch over them, to build, and to plant, says the Lord. 
\v 29 In those days they will certainly not say, The fathers ate a sour grape, and the children's teeth were set on edge. 
\v 30 But every one will die in his own sin; and the teeth of him who eats the sour grape will be set on edge. 
\p
\v 31 Behold, days are coming, says the Lord, when I will make a new covenant with the house of Israel, and with the house of Judah: 
\v 32 \x + \xo 38:32 \xt Heb 8:9\x*not according to the covenant which I made with their fathers in the day when I took hold of their hand to bring them out of the land of Egypt; for they didn't remain in my covenant, and I disregarded them, says the Lord. 
\v 33 For this is my covenant which I will make with the house of Israel; after those days, says the Lord, I will surely put my laws into their mind, and write them on their hearts; and I will be their God, and they will be my people. 
\v 34 They will surely not teach every one his \add fellow\add* citizen, and every one his brother, saying, Know the Lord: for all will know me, from the least of them to the greatest of them: for I will be merciful to their iniquities, and their sins I will remember no more. 
\p
\v 35 Though the sky should be raised to a \add greater\add* height, says the Lord, and though the ground of the earth should be sunk \add lower\add* beneath, yet I will not cast off the family of Israel, says the Lord, for all that they have done. 
\p
\v 36 Thus says the Lord, who gives the sun for a light by day, the moon and the stars for a light by night, and \add makes\add* a roaring in the sea, so that the waves of it roar; the Lord Almighty is his name: 
\v 37 if these ordinances cease from before me, says the Lord, then will the family of Israel cease to be a nation before me forever. 
\p
\v 38 Behold, days are coming, says the Lord, when the city will be built to the Lord from the tower of Anameel to the gate of the corner. 
\v 39 The measurement of it will proceed in front of them as far as the hills of Gareb, and it will be surrounded with a circular wall of choice stones. 
\v 40 All the Asaremoth even to Nachal Kedron, as far as the corner of the horse-gate eastward, will be holiness to the Lord; and it will not fail any more, and will not be destroyed forever. 
\c 39 
\p
\v 1 The word that came from the Lord to Jeremiah in the tenth year of king Zedekiah, this is the eighteenth year of king Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon. 
\p
\v 2 The host of the king of Babylon had made a rampart against Jerusalem: and Jeremiah was kept in the court of the prison, which is in the king's house; 
\v 3 in which king Zedekiah \add had\add* shut him up, saying, Why do you prophesy, saying, Thus says the Lord, Behold, I \add will\add* give this city into the hands of the king of Babylon, and he will take it; 
\v 4 and Zedekiah will by no means be delivered out of the hand of the Chaldeans, for he will certainly be given up into the hands of the king of Babylon, and his mouth will speak to his mouth, and his eyes will look upon his eyes; 
\v 5 and Zedekiah will go into Babylon, and dwell there? 
\p
\v 6 \sc And the Word of the Lord came to Jeremiah, saying,\sc* 
\v 7 Behold, Anameel the son of Salom your father's brother is coming to you, saying, Buy my field that is in Anathoth: for you \add have\add* the right to take \add it\add* as a purchase. 
\p
\v 8 So Anameel the son of Salom my father's brother came to me into the court of the prison, and said, Buy my field that is in the land of Benjamin, in Anathoth: for you \add have\add* a right to buy it, and you are the elder. So I knew that it was the word of the Lord. 
\v 9 I bought the field from Anameel the son of my father's brother, and I weighed him seventeen shekels of silver. 
\v 10 I wrote \add it\add* in a book, and sealed \add it\add*, and took the testimony of witnesses, and weighed the money in the balance. 
\v 11 I took the book of the purchase that was sealed; 
\v 12 and I gave it to Baruch son of Nerias, son of Maasæas, in the sight of Anameel my father's brother's son, and in the sight of the men who stood by and wrote in the book of the purchase, and in the sight of the Jews who were in the court of the prison. 
\v 13 I charged Baruch in their presence, saying, Thus says the Lord Almighty; 
\v 14 Take this book of the purchase, and the book that has been read; and put it into an earthen vessel, that it may remain many days. 
\v 15 For thus says the Lord; There will yet be fields and houses and vineyards bought in this land. 
\p
\v 16 I prayed to the Lord after I had given the book of the purchase to Baruch the son of Nerias, saying, 
\p
\v 17 O \add ever\add* living Lord! You have made the heaven and the earth by your great power, and with your high and lofty arm: nothing can be hidden from you. 
\v 18 Granting mercy to thousands, and recompensing the sins of the fathers into the bosoms of their children after them: the great, the strong God; 
\v 19 the Lord of great counsel, and mighty in deeds, the great Almighty God, and Lord of great name: your eyes are upon the ways of the children of men, to give to every one according to his way: 
\v 20 who have worked signs and wonders in the land of Egypt even to this day, and in Israel, and among the inhabitants of the earth; and you made a name for yourself, as at this day; 
\v 21 and you brought your people Israel out of the land of Egypt with signs, and with wonders, with a mighty hand, and with a high arm, and with great sights; 
\v 22 and you gave them this land, which you swore \add to give\add* to their fathers, a land flowing with milk and honey; 
\v 23 and they went in, and took it; but they didn't listen to your voice, and didn't walk in your ordinances; they did none of the things which you commanded them, and they caused all these calamities to happen to them. 
\v 24 Behold, a multitude has come against the city to take it; and the city is given into the hands of the Chaldeans who fight against it, by the power of the sword, and the famine: as you have spoken, so has it happened. 
\v 25 You say to me, Buy the field for money; and I wrote a book, and sealed \add it\add*, and took the testimony of witnesses: and the city is given into the hands of the Chaldeans. 
\p
\v 26 The word of the Lord came to me, saying, 
\p
\v 27 I am the Lord, the God of all flesh: will anything be hidden from me! 
\v 28 Therefore thus says the Lord God of Israel; This city will certainly be delivered into the hands of the king of Babylon, and he will take it: 
\v 29 and the Chaldeans will come to war against this city, and they will burn this city with fire, and will burn down the houses where they burnt incense on the roofs to Baal, and poured drink-offerings to other gods, to provoke me. 
\v 30 For the children of Israel and the children of Judah alone did evil in my sight from their youth. 
\v 31 For this city was \add obnoxious\add* to my anger and my wrath, from the day that they built it even to this day; that I should remove it from my presence, 
\v 32 because of all the wickedness of the children of Israel and Judah, which they worked to provoke me, they and their kings, and their princes, and their priests, and their prophets, the men of Judah, and the dwellers in Jerusalem. 
\v 33 They turned their back to me, and not their face: because I taught them early in the morning, but they listened no more to receive instruction. 
\v 34 They set their pollutions in the house on which my name was called, by their uncleannesses. 
\v 35 They built to Baal the altars that are in the valley of the son of Ennom, to offer their sons and their daughters to king Moloch; which things I didn't command them, neither did it come into my mind that they should do this abomination, to cause Judah to sin. 
\p
\v 36 Now thus has the Lord God of Israel said concerning this city, of which you say, It will be delivered into the hands of the king of Babylon by the sword, and by famine, and banishment. 
\v 37 Behold, I \add will\add* gather them out of every land, where I have scattered them in my anger, and my wrath, and great fury; and I will bring them back into this place, and will cause them to dwell safely: 
\v 38 and they will be my people, and I will be their God. 
\v 39 I will give them another way, and another heart, to fear me continually, and \add that\add* for good to them and their children after them. 
\v 40 I will make with them an everlasting covenant, which I will by no means turn away from them, and I will put my fear into their heart, so they may not depart from me. 
\v 41 I will visit \add them\add* to do them good, and I will plant them in this land in faithfulness, and with all my heart, and with all \add my\add* soul. 
\p
\v 42 For thus says the Lord; As I have brought upon this people all these great evils, so will I bring upon them all the good things which I pronounced upon them. 
\v 43 There will yet be fields bought in the land, of which you say, It will be destitute of man and beast; and they are delivered into the hands of the Chaldeans. 
\v 44 They will buy fields for money, and you will write a book, and seal \add it\add*, and will take the testimony of witnesses in the land of Benjamin, and round about Jerusalem, and in the cities of Judah, and in the cities of the mountain, and in the cities of the plain, and in the cities of the south: for I will turn their captivity. 
\c 40 
\p
\v 1 The word of the Lord came to Jeremiah the second time, when he was still bound in the court of the prison, saying, 
\p
\v 2 Thus says the Lord, who made the earth and formed it, to establish it; the Lord is his name; 
\v 3 Cry to me, and I will answer you, and I will declare to you great and mighty things, which you know not. 
\v 4 For thus says the Lord concerning the houses of this city, and concerning the houses of the king of Judah, which have been pulled down for mounds and fortifications, 
\v 5 to fight against the Chaldeans, and to fill it with the corpses of men, whom I struck in my anger and my wrath, and turned away my face from them, for all their wickedness: 
\v 6 Behold, I bring upon her healing and cure, and I will show \add myself\add* to them, and will heal her, and make both peace and security. 
\p
\v 7 I will turn the captivity of Judah, and the captivity of Israel, and will build them, even as before. 
\v 8 I will cleanse them from all their iniquities, by which they have sinned against me, and will not remember their sins, by which they have sinned against me, and revolted from me. 
\v 9 It will be for joy and praise, and for glory to all the people of the earth, who will hear all the good that I will do: and they will fear and be provoked for all the good things and for all the peace which I will bring upon them. 
\p
\v 10 Thus says the Lord; There will yet be heard in this place, of which you say, It is destitute of men and cattle, in the cities of Judah, and in the streets of Jerusalem, \add the places\add* that have been made desolate for want of men and cattle, 
\v 11 the voice of gladness, and the voice of joy, the voice of the bridegroom, and the voice of the bride, the voice of men saying, Give thanks to the Lord Almighty: for the Lord is good; for his mercy \add endures\add* forever: and they will bring gifts into the house of the Lord; for I will turn all the captivity of that land as before, said the Lord. 
\v 12 Thus says the Lord of hosts; There will yet be in this place, that is desert for want of man and beast, in all its cities, resting-places for shepherds causing their flocks to lie down. 
\v 13 In the cities of the hill country, and in the cities of the valley, and in the cities of the south, and in the land of Benjamin, and in the \add cities\add* around Jerusalem, and in the cities of Judah, flocks will yet pass under the hand of him who numbers \add them\add*, says the Lord. 
\c 41 
\p
\v 1 The word that came to Jeremiah from the Lord (now Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon, and all his army, and all the country of his dominion, were warring against Jerusalem, and against all the cities of Judah,) saying, 
\p
\v 2 Thus has the Lord said; Go to Zedekiah king of Judah, and you will say to him, Thus has the Lord said, This city will certainly be delivered into the hands of the king of Babylon, and he will take it, and will burn it with fire: 
\v 3 and you will not escape out of his hand, but will certainly be taken, and will be given into his hands; and your eyes will see his eyes, and you will enter into Babylon. 
\p
\v 4 But hear the word of the Lord, O Zedekiah king of Judah; Thus says the Lord, 
\v 5 You will die in peace: and as they wept for your fathers who reigned before you, they will weep also for you, \add saying\add*, Ah lord! And they will lament for you down to the grave: for I have spoken the word, said the Lord. 
\p
\v 6 Jeremiah spoke to king Zedekiah all these words in Jerusalem. 
\v 7 The host of the king of Babylon warred against Jerusalem, and against the cities of Judah, and against Lachis, and against Azeca: for these strong cities were left among the cities of Judah. 
\p
\v 8 The word that came from the Lord to Jeremiah, after king Zedekiah had concluded a covenant with the people, to proclaim a release; 
\v 9 that every one should set at liberty his servant, and every one his handmaid, the Hebrew man and Hebrew woman, that no man of Judah should be a bondman. 
\v 10 Then all the nobles, and all the people who had entered into the covenant, \add engaging\add* to set free every one his man-servant, and every one his maiden, turned, 
\v 11 and gave them over to be men-servants and maiden-servants. 
\p
\v 12 The word of the Lord came to Jeremiah, saying, 
\v 13 Thus says the Lord; I made a covenant with your fathers in the day wherein I took them out of the land of Egypt, out of the house of bondage, saying, 
\v 14 When six years are accomplished, you will set free your brother the Hebrew, who will be sold to you: for he will serve you six years, and \add then\add* you will let him go free: but they didn't listen to me, and didn't incline their ear. 
\v 15 This day they turned to do that which was right in my sight, to proclaim every one the release of his neighbour; and they had concluded a covenant before me, in the house whereon my name is called. 
\v 16 But you turned and profaned my name, to bring back every one his servant, and every one his handmaid, whom you had sent free \add and\add* at their own disposal, to be to you men-servants and maiden-servants. 
\p
\v 17 Therefore thus said the Lord; You have not listened to me, to proclaim a release every one to his neighbour: behold, I proclaim a release to you, to the sword, and to the pestilence, and to the famine; and I will give you up to dispersion \add among\add* all the kingdoms of the earth. 
\v 18 I will give the men who have transgressed my covenant, who have not kept my covenant, which they made before me, the calf which they prepared to sacrifice with it, 
\v 19 the princes of Judah, and the men in power, and the priests, and the people; 
\v 20 I will even give them to their enemies, and their carcases will be food for the birds of the sky and for the wild beasts of the earth. 
\v 21 I will give Zedekiah king of Judea, and their princes, into the hands of their enemies, and the host of the king of Babylon \add will come upon\add* those who run away from them. 
\v 22 Behold, I \add will\add* give command, says the Lord, and will bring them back to this land; and they will fight against it, and take it, and burn it with fire, and the cities of Judah; and I will make them desolate without inhabitants. 
\c 42 
\p
\v 1 \sc The Word that came to Jeremiah\sc* from the Lord in the days of Joakim, king of Judah, saying, 
\v 2 Go to the house of the Archabin, and you will bring them to the house of the Lord, into one of the courts, and give them wine to drink. 
\p
\v 3 So I brought forth Jechonias the son of Jeremin the son of Chabasin, and his brothers, and his sons, and all the family of the Archabin; 
\v 4 and I brought them into the house of the Lord, into the chamber of the sons of Joanan, the son of Ananias, the son of Godolias, a man of God, who dwells near the house of the princes who are over the house of Maasæas the son of Selom, who kept the court. 
\v 5 I set before them a jar of wine, and cups, and I said, Drink wine. 
\p
\v 6 But they said, We will surely not drink wine, for our father Jonadab the son of Rechab commanded us, saying, You will surely not drink wine, \add neither\add* you, nor your sons forever: 
\v 7 nor will you at all build houses, nor sow any seed, nor will you have a vineyard: for you will dwell in tents all your days; that you may live many days upon the land, in which you sojourn. 
\v 8 We listened to the voice of Jonadab our father, so as to drink no wine all our days, we, and our wives, and our sons, and our daughters; 
\v 9 and so as to build no houses to dwell in: and we have had no vineyard, nor field, nor seed: 
\v 10 but we have dwelt in tents, and have listened, and done according to all that Jonadab our father commanded us. 
\v 11 It happened, when Nebuchadnezzar came up against the land, that we said we would come in; and we entered into Jerusalem, for fear of the host of the Chaldeans, and for fear of the host of the Assyrians: and we dwelt there. 
\p
\v 12 The word of the Lord came to me, saying, 
\v 13 Thus says the Lord, Go, and say to the men of Judah, and to those who dwell in Jerusalem, Will you not receive correction to listen to my words? 
\v 14 The sons of Jonadab the son of Rechab have kept the word which he commanded his children, that they should drink no wine; and they have not drunk \add it\add*: but I spoke to you early, and you didn't listen. 
\v 15 I sent to you my servants the prophets, saying, Turn every one from his evil way, and amend your practices, and don't go after other gods to serve them, and you will dwell upon the land which I gave to you and to your fathers: but you didn't incline your ears, and didn't listen. 
\v 16 The sons of Jonadab the son of Rechab have kept the command of their father; but this people has not listened to me. 
\v 17 Therefore thus says the Lord; Behold, I \add will\add* bring upon Judah and upon the inhabitants of Jerusalem all the evils which I pronounced against them. 
\p
\v 18 Therefore thus says the Lord; Since the sons of Jonadab the son of Rechab have listened to the command of their father, to do as their father commanded them: 
\v 19 there will never be wanting a man of the sons of Jonadab the son of Rechab to stand before my face while the earth remains. 
\c 43 
\p
\v 1 \sc In the fourth Year of Joakim\sc* son of Josiah king of Judah, the word of the Lord came to me, saying, 
\p
\v 2 Take a roll of a book, and write upon it all the words which I spoke to you against Jerusalem, and against Judah, and against all the nations, from the day when I spoke to you, from the days of Josiah king of Judah, even to this day. 
\v 3 Perhaps the house of Judah will hear all the evils which I purpose to do to them; so they may turn from their evil way; and \add so\add* I will be merciful to their iniquities and their sins. 
\p
\v 4 So Jeremiah called Baruch the son of Nerias: and he wrote from the mouth of Jeremiah all the words of the Lord, which he had spoken to him, on a roll of a book. 
\v 5 Jeremiah commanded Baruch, saying, I am in prison; I cannot enter into the house of the Lord: 
\v 6 so you will read from this roll in the ears of the people in the house of the Lord, on the fast day; and in the ears of all Judah that come out of their cities, you will read to them. 
\v 7 Perhaps their supplication will come before the Lord, and they will turn from their evil way: for great is the wrath and the anger of the Lord, which he has pronounced against this people. 
\p
\v 8 Baruch did according to all that Jeremiah commanded him—reading from the book the words of the Lord in the Lord's house. 
\v 9 It happened in the eighth year of king Joakim, in the ninth month, all the people in Jerusalem, and the house of Judah, proclaimed a fast before the Lord. 
\v 10 Baruch read from the book the words of Jeremiah in the house of the Lord, in the house of Gamarias son of Saphan the scribe, in the upper court, in the entrance of the new gate of the house of the Lord, and in the ears of all the people. 
\p
\v 11 Micah the son of Gamarias the son of Saphan heard all the words of the Lord, out of the book. 
\v 12 He went down to the king's house, into the house of the scribe: and, behold, there were sitting there all the princes, Elisama the scribe, and Dalæas the son of Selemias, and Jonathan the son of Acchobor, and Gamarias the son of Saphan, and Zedekiah the son of Ananias, and all the princes. 
\v 13 Micah reported to them all the words which he had heard Baruch reading in the ears of the people. 
\p
\v 14 All the princes sent to Baruch son of Nerias Judin the son of Nathanias, the son of Selemias, the son of Chusi, saying, Take in your hand the roll from which you read in the ears of the people, and come. So Baruch took the roll, and went down to them. 
\v 15 They said to him, Read \add it\add* again in our ears. And Baruch read \add it\add*. 
\v 16 It happened, when they \add had\add* heard all the words, \add that\add* they took counsel each with his neighbour, and said, Let us by all means tell the king all these words. 
\v 17 They asked Baruch, saying, Where did you write all these words? 
\v 18 Baruch said, Jeremiah told me from his \add own\add* mouth all these words, and I wrote them in a book. 
\v 19 They said to Baruch, Go, and hide, you and Jeremiah; let no man know where you \add are\add*. 
\p
\v 20 They went in to the king into the court, and gave the roll \add to one\add* to keep in the house of Elisama; and they told the king all these words. 
\v 21 The king sent Judin to fetch the roll: and he took it out of the house of Elisama: and Judin read in the ears of the king, and in the ears of all the princes who stood round the king. 
\v 22 Now the king was sitting in the winter house: and \add there was\add* a fire on the hearth before him. 
\v 23 It happened when Judin had read three or four leaves, he cut them off with a penknife, and cast \add them\add* into the fire that was on the hearth, until the whole roll was consumed in the fire that was on the hearth. 
\v 24 The king and his servants who heard all these words didn't seek \add the Lord\add*, and didn't tear their garments. 
\v 25 But Elnathan and Godolias suggested to the king that he should burn the roll. 
\p
\v 26 The king commanded Jeremeel the king's son, and Saræas the son of Esriel, to take Baruch and Jeremiah: but they were hidden. 
\p
\v 27 Then the word of the Lord came to Jeremiah, after the king had burnt the roll, \add even\add* all the words which Baruch wrote from the mouth of Jeremiah, saying, 
\v 28 Again take another roll, and write all the words that were on the roll, which king Joakim has burnt. 
\v 29 You will say, Thus says the Lord; You have burnt this roll, saying, Why have you written therein, saying, The king of Babylon will certainly come in, and destroy this land, and man and cattle will fail from off it? 
\p
\v 30 Therefore thus says the Lord concerning Joakim king of Judah; He will not have \add a man\add* to sit on the throne of David: and his carcase will be cast forth in the heat by day, and in the frost by night. 
\v 31 I will visit him, and his family, and his servants: and I will bring upon him, and upon the inhabitants of Jerusalem, and upon the land of Judah, all the evils which I spoke of to them; and they didn't listen. 
\p
\v 32 Baruch took another roll, and wrote upon it from the mouth of Jeremiah all the words of the book which Joakim had burnt: and there were yet more words added to it like the former. 
\c 44 
\p
\v 1 Zedekiah the son of Josiah reigned instead of Joakim, whom Nebuchadnezzar appointed to reign over Judah. 
\v 2 He and his servants and the people of the land didn't listen to the words of the Lord, which he spoke by Jeremiah. 
\p
\v 3 King Zedekiah sent Joachal son of Selemias and Zephaniah the priest son of Maasæas to Jeremiah, saying, Pray now for us to the Lord. 
\v 4 Now Jeremiah came and went through the midst of the city: for they \add had\add* not put him into the house of the prison. 
\v 5 The host of Pharaoh had come forth out of Egypt; and the Chaldeans heard the report of them, and they went up from Jerusalem. 
\p
\v 6 The word of the Lord came to Jeremiah, saying, 
\v 7 Thus said the Lord; Thus will you say to the king of Judah who sent to you, to seek me; Behold, the army of Pharaoh which has come forth to help you: they will return to the land of Egypt: 
\v 8 and the Chaldeans themselves will turn again, and fight against this city, and take it, and burn it with fire. 
\v 9 For thus says the Lord; Don't suppose in your hearts, saying, The Chaldeans will certainly depart from us: for they will not depart. 
\v 10 Though you should strike the whole host of the Chaldeans who fight against you, and there should be left a few wounded \add men\add*, these should rise up each in his place, and burn this city with fire. 
\p
\v 11 It happened, when the host of the Chaldeans had gone up from Jerusalem for fear of the host of Pharaoh, 
\v 12 that Jeremiah went out from Jerusalem to go into the land of Benjamin, to buy from there \add a property\add* among the people. 
\v 13 He was in the gate of Benjamin, and \add there was\add* there a man with whom he lodged, Saruia the son of Selemias, the son of Ananias; and he caught Jeremiah, saying, You are fleeing to the Chaldeans. 
\v 14 He said, \add It is\add* false; I do not flee to the Chaldeans. But he didn't listen to him; and Saruia caught Jeremiah, and brought him to the princes. 
\v 15 The princes were very angry with Jeremiah, and struck him, and sent him into the house of Jonathan the scribe: for they had made this a prison. 
\p
\v 16 So Jeremiah came into the dungeon, and into the cells, and he remained there many days. 
\v 17 Then Zedekiah sent, and called him; and the king asked him secretly, saying, Is there a word from the Lord? And he said, There is: you will be delivered into the hands of the king of Babylon. 
\v 18 Jeremiah said to the king, How have I wronged you, or your servants, or this people, that you put me in prison? 
\v 19 Where are your prophets who prophesied to you saying, The king of Babylon will not come against this land? 
\v 20 Now therefore, my lord the king, let my supplication come before your face: and why do you send me back to the house of Jonathan the scribe? And don't let me on any account die there. 
\v 21 Then the king commanded, and they cast him into the prison, and gave him a loaf a day out of the place where they bake, until the bread failed out of the city. So Jeremiah continued in the court of the prison. 
\c 45 
\p
\v 1 Saphanias the son of Nathan, and Godolias the son of Paschor, and Joachal the son of Semelias, heard the words which Jeremiah spoke to the people, saying, 
\p
\v 2 Thus says the Lord; He who remains in this city will die by the sword, and by the famine: but he who goes out to the Chaldeans will live; and his soul will be given him for a found treasure, and he will live. 
\v 3 For thus says the Lord; This city will certainly be delivered into the hands of the host of the king of Babylon, and they will take it. 
\v 4 They said to the king, Let that man, we pray you, be killed, for he weakens the hands of the fighting men who are left in the city, and the hands of all the people, speaking to them according to these words: for this man does not prophesy peace to this people, but evil. 
\v 5 Then the king said, Behold, he is in your hands. For the king could not resist them. 
\v 6 They cast him into the dungeon of Melchias the king's son, which was in the court of the prison; and they let him down into the pit: and there was no water in the pit, but mud: and he was in the mud. 
\p
\v 7 Abdemelech the Ethiopian heard, (now he was in the king's household,) that they \add had\add* put Jeremiah into the dungeon; and the king was in the gate of Benjamin: 
\v 8 and he went out to him, and spoke to the king and said, 
\v 9 You have done evil in what you have done to kill this man with hunger: for there is no more bread in the city. 
\v 10 The king commanded Abdemelech, saying, Take with you hence thirty men, and bring him up out of the dungeon, that he die not. 
\v 11 So Abdemelech took the men, and went into the underground \add part of the\add* king's house, and took from there old rags and old ropes, and threw them to Jeremiah into the dungeon. 
\v 12 He said, Put these under the ropes. And Jeremiah did so. 
\v 13 They drew him with the ropes, and lifted him out of the dungeon: and Jeremiah remained in the court of the prison. 
\p
\v 14 Then the king sent, and called him to himself into the house of Aselisel, which was in the house of the Lord: and the king said to him, I will ask you a question, and I pray you hide nothing from me. 
\p
\v 15 Jeremiah said to the king, If I tell you, will you not certainly put me to death? And if I give you counsel, you will not at all listen to me. 
\v 16 The king swore to him, saying, \add As\add* the Lord lives who gave us this soul, I will not kill you, neither I will give you into the hands of these men. 
\p
\v 17 Jeremiah said to him, Thus says the Lord; If you will indeed go forth to the captains of the king of Babylon, your soul will live, and this city will certainly not be burnt with fire; and you will live, and your house. 
\v 18 But if you will not go forth, this city will be delivered into the hands of the Chaldeans, and they will burn it with fire, and you will by no means escape. 
\p
\v 19 The king said to Jeremiah, I consider the Jews who have gone over to the Chaldeans, lest they deliver me into their hands, and they mock me. 
\p
\v 20 Jeremiah said, They will certainly not deliver you up. Hear the word of the Lord which I speak to you; and it will be better for you, and your soul will live. 
\v 21 But if you will not go forth, this is the word which the Lord has shown me. 
\v 22 And, behold, all the women that are left in the house of the king of Judah were brought forth to the princes of the king of Babylon; and they said, The men who were at peace with you have deceived you, and will prevail against you; and they will cause your foot to slide and fail, they have turned back from you. 
\v 23 They will bring forth your wives and your children to the Chaldeans: and you will by no means escape, for you will be taken by the hand of the king of Babylon, and this city will be burnt. 
\p
\v 24 Then the king said to him, Let no man know \add any\add* of these words, and certainly you will not die. 
\v 25 If the princes will hear that I have spoken to you, and they come to you, and say to you, Tell us, what said the king to you? Hide \add it\add* not from us, and we will certainly not kill you, and what said the king to you? 
\v 26 Then you will say to them, I brought my supplication before the presence of the king, that he would not send me back into the house of Jonathan, that I should die there. 
\p
\v 27 All the princes came to Jeremiah, and asked him: and he told them according to all these words, which the king had commanded him. And they were silent, because the word of the Lord was not heard. 
\v 28 Jeremiah remained in the court of the prison, until the time when Jerusalem was taken. 
\c 46 
\p
\v 1 It happened in the ninth month of Zedekiah king of Judah, \add that\add* Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon came, and all his host, against Jerusalem, and they besieged it. 
\v 2 In the eleventh year of Zedekiah, in the fourth month, on the ninth day of the month, the city was broken \add up\add*. 
\v 3 All the leaders of the king of Babylon went in, and sat in the middle gate, Marganasar, and Samagoth, and Nabusachar, and Nabusaris, Nagargas, Naserrabamath, and the rest of the leaders of the king of Babylon, 
\v 14 and they sent, and took Jeremiah out of the court of the prison, and gave him \add in charge\add* to Godolias the son of Achicam, the son of Saphan: and they brought him out, and he sat among the people. 
\p
\v 15 The word of the Lord came to Jeremiah in the court of the prison, saying, 
\v 16 Go and say to Abdemelech the Ethiopian, Thus said the Lord God of Israel; Behold, I \add will\add* bring my words upon this city for evil, and not for good. 
\v 17 But I will save you in that day, and I will by no means deliver you into the hands of the men before whom you are afraid. 
\v 18 For I will surely save you, and you will by no means fall by the sword; and you will find your life, because you did trust in me, says the Lord. 
\c 47 
\p
\v 1 The word that came from the Lord to Jeremiah, after that Nabuzardan the captain of the guard had let him go out of Rama, when he had taken him in manacles among the captivity of Judah, \add even\add* those who were carried to Babylon. 
\p
\v 2 The chief captain of the guard took him, and said to him, The Lord your God has pronounced all these evils upon this place: 
\v 3 and the Lord has done it; because you sinned against him, and didn't listen to his voice. 
\v 4 Behold, I have loosed you from the manacles that were upon your hands. If it seem good to you to go with me to Babylon, then will I set my eyes upon you. 
\v 5 But if not, depart; return to Godolias the son of Achicam, the son of Saphan, whom the king of Babylon has appointed governor in the land of Judah, and dwell with him among the people in the land of Judah: to whatever places it seems good in your eyes to go, do you even go. And the captain of the guard made him presents, and let him go. 
\v 6 He came to Godolias to Massepha, and dwelt among his people that was left in the land. 
\p
\v 7 All the leaders of the host that was in the country, they and their men, heard that the king of Babylon had appointed Godolias \add governor\add* in the land, and they committed to him the men and their wives, whom \add Nebuchadnezzar had\add* not removed to Babylon. 
\v 8 There came to Godolias to Massepha Ismael the son of Nathanias, and Joanan son of Caree, and Saræas the son of Thanaemeth, and the sons of Jophe the Netophathite, and Ezonias son of the Mochathite, they and their men. 
\p
\v 9 Godolias swore to them and to their men, saying, Don't be afraid before the children of the Chaldeans: dwell in the land, and serve the king of Babylon, and it will be better for you. 
\v 10 And, behold, I dwell in your presence at Massepha, to stand before the Chaldeans who will come against you: and do you gather grapes, and fruits, and oil, and put \add them\add* into your vessels, and dwell in the cities which you have obtained possession of. 
\p
\v 11 All the Jews that were in Moab, and among the children of Ammon, and those \add that were\add* in Idumea, and those \add that were\add* in all \add the rest of\add* the country, heard that the king of Babylon \add had\add* granted a remnant to Judah, and that he had appointed over them Godolias the son of Achicam. 
\v 12 They came to Godolias into the land of Judah, to Massepha, and gathered grapes, and very much summer fruit, and oil. 
\p
\v 13 Joanan the son of Caree, and all the leaders of the host, who were in the fields, came to Godolias to Massepha, 
\v 14 and said to him, Do you indeed know that king Beleissa son of Ammon has sent Ismael to you to kill you? But Godolias didn't believe them. 
\v 15 Joanan said to Godolias secretly in Massepha, I will go now and strike Ismael, and let no man know \add it\add*; lest he kill you, and all the Jews who are gathered to you be dispersed, and the remnant of Judah perish. 
\v 16 But Godolias said to Joanan, Do not the thing, for you speak lies concerning Ismael. 
\c 48 
\p
\v 1 Now it happened in the seventh month that Ismael the son of Nathanias the son of Eleasa of the seed royal, came, and ten men with him, to Godolias to Massepha: and they ate bread there together. 
\v 2 Ismael rose up, and the ten men who were with him, and struck Godolias, whom the king of Babylon had appointed \add governor\add* over the land, 
\v 3 and all the Jews who were with him in Massepha, and all the Chaldeans who were found there. 
\p
\v 4 It happened on the second day after he had struck Godolias, and no man knew \add of it\add*, 
\v 5 that there came men from Sychem, and from Salem, and from Samaria, \add even\add* eighty men, having their beards shaven, and their clothes rent, and beating their breasts, and \add they had\add* manna and frankincense in their hands, to bring \add them\add* into the house of the Lord. 
\v 6 Ismael went out to meet them; \add and\add* they went on and wept: and he said to them, Come in to Godolias. 
\v 7 It happened, when they had entered into the midst of the city, \add that\add* he killed them \add and cast them\add* into a pit. 
\v 8 But ten men were found there, and they said to Ismael, Kill us not: for we have treasures in the field, wheat and barley, honey and oil. So he passed by, and killed them not among their brothers. 
\p
\v 9 Now the pit into which Ismael cast all whom he struck, is the great pit, which king Asa had made for fear of Baasa king of Israel: \add even\add* this Ismael filled with killed men. 
\p
\v 10 Ismael brought back all the people who were left in Massepha, and the king's daughter, whom the captain of the guard had committed in charge to Godolias the son of Achicam: and he went away beyond the children of Ammon. 
\p
\v 11 Joanan the son of Careë, and all the leaders of the host who were with him, heard of all the evil deeds which Ismael had done. 
\v 12 They brought all their army, and went to fight against him, and found him near much water in Gabaon. 
\v 13 It happened, when all the people that was with Ismael saw Joanan, and the leaders of the host that was with him, 
\v 14 that they returned to Joanan. 
\v 15 But Ismael escaped with eight men and went to the children of Ammon. 
\p
\v 16 Joanan, and all the leaders of the host who were with him, took all the remnant of the people, whom he \add had\add* brought back from Ismael, mighty men in war, and the women, and the other \add property\add*, and the eunuchs, whom they \add had\add* brought back from Gabaon: 
\v 17 and they departed, and dwelt in Gaberoch-amaa, that is by Bethlehem, to go into Egypt, for fear of the Chaldeans: 
\v 18 for they were afraid of them, because Ismael had struck Godolias, whom the king of Babylon made \add governor\add* in the land. 
\c 49 
\p
\v 1 Then came all the leaders of the host, and Joanan, and Azariah the son of Maasæas, and all the people great and small, 
\v 2 to Jeremiah the prophet, and said to him, Let now our supplication come before your face, and pray you to the Lord your God for this remnant; for we are left few out of many, as your eyes see. 
\v 3 Let the Lord your God declare to us the way wherein we should walk, and the thing which we should do. 
\p
\v 4 Jeremiah said to them, I have heard \add you\add*; behold, I will pray for you to the Lord our God, according to your words; and it will come to pass, \add that\add* whatever word the Lord God will answer, I will declare \add it\add* to you; I will not hide anything from you. 
\p
\v 5 They said to Jeremiah, Let the Lord be between us for a just and faithful witness, if we do not according to every word which the Lord will send to us. 
\v 6 Whether \add it be\add* good, or whether \add it be\add* evil, we will listen to the voice of the Lord our God, to whom we send you; that it may be well with us, because we will listen to the voice of the Lord our God. 
\p
\v 7 It happened after ten days, \add that\add* the word of the Lord came to Jeremiah. 
\v 8 He called Joanan, and the leaders of the host, and all the people from the least even to the greatest, 
\v 9 and he said to them, Thus says the Lord; 
\v 10 If you will indeed dwell in this land, I will build you, and will not pull \add you\add* down, but will plant you, and certainly not pluck you up: for I have ceased from the calamities which I brought upon you. 
\v 11 Don't be afraid of the king of Babylon, of whom you are afraid; don't be afraid of him, says the Lord: for I am with you, to deliver you, and save you out of their hand. 
\v 12 I will grant you mercy, and pity you, and will restore you to your land. 
\p
\v 13 But if you say, We will not dwell in this land, that we may not listen to the voice of the Lord; 
\v 14 for we will go into the land of Egypt, and we will see no war, and will not hear the sound of a trumpet, and we will not hunger for bread; and there we will dwell: 
\v 15 then hear the word of the Lord; thus says the Lord; 
\v 16 If you set your face toward Egypt, and go in there to dwell; then it will be, \add that\add* the sword which you fear will find you in the land of Egypt, and the famine to which you have regard, will overtake you, \add coming\add* after you in Egypt; and there you will die. 
\v 17 All the men, and all the strangers who have set their face toward the land of Egypt to dwell there, will be consumed by the sword, and by the famine: and there will not one of them escape from the evils which I bring upon them. 
\p
\v 18 For thus says the Lord; As my wrath has dropped upon the inhabitants of Jerusalem, so will my wrath drop upon you, when you have entered into Egypt: and you will be a desolation, and under the power of others, and a curse and a reproach: and you will no more see this place. 
\p
\v 19 \add These are the words\add* which the Lord has spoken concerning you the remnant of Judah; Don't you enter into Egypt: and now know you for a certainty, 
\v 20 that you have worked wickedness in your hearts, when you sent me, saying, Pray you for us to the Lord; and according to all that the Lord will speak to you we will do. 
\v 21 You have not listened to the voice of the Lord, with which he sent me to you. 
\v 22 Now therefore you will perish by sword and by famine, in the place which you desire to go into to dwell there. 
\c 50 
\p
\v 1 It happened, when Jeremiah ceased speaking to the people all the words of the Lord, \add for\add* which the Lord had sent him to them, \add even\add* all these words, 
\v 2 that Azariah son of Maasæas spoke, and Joanan, the son of Careë, and all the men who had spoken to Jeremiah, saying, \add It is\add* false: the Lord has not sent you to us, saying, Don't enter into Egypt to dwell there: 
\v 3 but Baruch the son of Nerias sets you against us, that you may deliver us into the hands of the Chaldeans, to kill us, and that we should be carried away captives to Babylon. 
\v 4 So Joanan, and all the leaders of the host, and all the people, refused to listen to the voice of the Lord, to dwell in the land of Judah. 
\p
\v 5 Joanan, and all the leaders of the host, took all the remnant of Judah, who had returned to dwell in the land; 
\v 6 the mighty men, and the women, and the children who were left, and the daughters of the king, and the souls which Nabuzardan had left with Godolias the son of Achicam, and Jeremiah the prophet, and Baruch the son of Nerias. 
\v 7 They came into Egypt: for they didn't listen to the voice of the Lord: and they entered into Taphnas. 
\p
\v 8 The word of the Lord came to Jeremiah in Taphnas, saying, 
\v 9 Take you great stones, and hide them in the entrance, at the gate of the house of Pharaoh in Taphnas, in the sight of the men of Judah: 
\v 10 and you will say, Thus has the Lord said; Behold, I \add will\add* send, and will bring Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon, and he will place his throne upon these stones which you have hidden, and he will lift up weapons against them. 
\v 11 He will enter in, and strike the land of Egypt, \add delivering\add* some for death to death; and some for captivity to captivity; and some for the sword to the sword. 
\v 12 He will kindle a fire in the houses of their gods, and will burn them, and will carry them away captives: and will search the land of Egypt, as a shepherd searches his garment; and he will go forth in peace. 
\v 13 He will break to pieces the pillars of Heliopolis that are in On, and will burn their houses with fire. 
\c 51 
\p
\v 1 \sc The Word that came to Jeremiah\sc* for all the Jews dwelling in the land of Egypt, and for those settled in Magdolo and in Taphnas, and in the land of Pathura, saying, 
\p
\v 2 Thus has the Lord God of Israel said; You have seen all the evils which I have brought upon Jerusalem, and upon the cities of Judah; and, behold, they are desolate without inhabitants, 
\v 3 because of their wickedness, which they have worked to provoke me, \add by\add* going to burn incense to other gods, whom you didn't know. 
\v 4 Yet I sent to you my servants the prophets early in the morning, and I sent, saying, Do not you this abominable thing which I hate. 
\p
\v 5 But they didn't listen to me, and inclined not their ear to turn from their wickedness, so as not to burn incense to foreign gods. 
\v 6 So my anger and my wrath dropped \add upon them\add*, and was kindled in the gates of Judah, and in the streets of Jerusalem; and they became a desolation and a waste, as at this day. 
\p
\v 7 Now thus has the Lord Almighty said, Why do you commit \add these\add* great evils against your souls? To cut off man and woman of you, infant and suckling from the midst of Judah, to the end that not one of you should be left; 
\v 8 by provoking me with the works of your hands, to burn incense to other gods in the land of Egypt, into which you entered to dwell there, that you might be cut off, and that you might become a curse and a reproach among all the nations of the earth? 
\v 9 Have you forgotten the sins of your fathers, and the sins of the kings of Judah, and the sins of your princes, and the sins of your wives, which they worked in the land of Judah, and in the streets of Jerusalem? 
\v 10 Have not ceased even to this day, and they have not kept to my ordinances, which I set before their fathers. 
\p
\v 11 Therefore thus says the Lord; Behold, I do set my face against \add you\add* 
\v 12 to destroy all the remnant who are in Egypt; and they will fall by the sword, and by famine, and will be consumed small and great: and they will be for reproach, and for destruction, and for a curse. 
\v 13 I will visit those who dwell in the land of Egypt, as I have visited Jerusalem, with sword and with famine: 
\v 14 and there will not one be preserved of the remnant of Judah who sojourn in the land of Egypt, to return to the land of Judah, to which they hope in their hearts to return: they will not return, but only those who escape. 
\p
\v 15 Then all the men who knew that their wives burned incense, and all the women, a great multitude, and all the people who dwelt in the land of Egypt, in Pathura, answered Jeremiah, saying, 
\p
\v 16 \add As for\add* the word which you have spoken to us in the name of the Lord, we will not listen to you. 
\v 17 For we will surely perform every word that will proceed out of our mouth, to burn incense to the queen of heaven, and to pour drink-offerings to her, as we and our fathers have done, and our kings and princes, in the cities of Judah, and in the streets of Jerusalem: and \add so\add* we were filled with bread, and were well, and saw no evils. 
\v 18 But since we left off to burn incense to the queen of heaven, we have all been brought low, and have been consumed by sword and by famine. 
\v 19 Because we burned incense to the queen of heaven, and poured drink-offerings to her, did we make cakes to her, and pour drink-offerings to her, without our husbands? 
\p
\v 20 Then Jeremiah answered all the people, the mighty men, and the women, and all the people who returned him \add these\add* words for answer, saying, 
\v 21 Did not the Lord remember the incense which you burned in the cities of Judah, and in the streets of Jerusalem, you, and your fathers, and your kings, and your princes, and the people of the land? And didn't come it into his heart? 
\v 22 The Lord could no longer bear \add you\add*, because of the wickedness of your doings, and because of your abominations which you worked; and so your land became a desolation and a waste, and a curse, as at this day; 
\v 23 because of your burning incense, and \add because\add* of the things wherein you sinned against the Lord: and you have not listened to the voice of the Lord, and have not walked in his ordinances, and in his law, and in his testimonies; and so these evils have come upon you. 
\p
\v 24 Jeremiah said to the people, and to the women, Hear the word of the Lord. 
\v 25 Thus has the Lord God of Israel said; You women have spoken with your mouth, and you fulfilled \add it\add* with your hands, saying, We will surely perform our vows that we have vowed, to burn incense to the queen of heaven, and to pour drink-offerings to her: full well did you keep to your vows, and you have indeed performed \add them\add*. 
\v 26 Therefore hear the word of the Lord, all Jews dwelling in the land of Egypt; Behold, I have sworn by my great name, says the Lord, my name will no longer be in the mouth of every Jew to say, The Lord lives, in all the land of Egypt. 
\v 27 For I have watched over them, to hurt them, and not to do them good: and all the Jews dwelling in the land of Egypt will perish by sword and by famine, until they are completely consumed. 
\v 28 Those who escape the sword will return to the land of Judah few in number, and the remnant of Judah, who have continued in the land \add of\add* Egypt to dwell there, will know whose word will stand. 
\p
\v 29 This \add will be\add* a sign to you, that I will visit you for evil. 
\v 30 Thus said the Lord; Behold, I \add will\add* give Uaphres king of Egypt into the hands of his enemy, and into the hands of one who seeks his life; as I gave Zedekiah king of Judah into the hands of Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon, his enemy, and who sought his life. 
\p
\v 31 \sc The Word which Jeremiah the Prophet\sc* spoke to Baruch son of Nerias, when he wrote these words in the book from the mouth of Jeremiah, in the fourth year of Joakim the son of Josiah king of Judah. 
\p
\v 32 Thus has the Lord said to you, O Baruch. 
\v 33 Because you have said, Alas! Alas! For the Lord has laid a grievous trouble upon me; I lay down in groaning, I found no rest; 
\v 34 say to him, Thus says the Lord; Behold, I pull down those whom I have built up, and I pluck up those whom I have planted. 
\v 35 Will you seek great things for yourself? Don't seek \add them\add*: for, behold, I bring evil upon all flesh, says the Lord: but I will give \add to you\add* your life for a spoil in every place where you will go. 
\c 52 
\p
\v 1 It was the twenty-first year of Zedekiah, when he began to reign, and he reigned eleven years in Jerusalem. And his mother's name was Amitaal, the daughter of Jeremiah, of Lobena. 
\p
\v 4 It happened in the ninth year of his reign, in the ninth month, on the tenth day of the month, \add that\add* Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon came, and all his host, against Jerusalem, and they made a rampart round it, and built a wall round about it with large stones. 
\p
\v 5 So the city was besieged, until the eleventh year of king Zedekiah, 
\v 6 on the ninth day of the month, and \add then\add* the famine was severe in the city, and there was no bread for the people of the land. 
\v 7 The city was broken up, and all the men of war went out by night by the way of the gate, between the wall and the outworks, which were by the king's garden; and the Chaldeans were by the city round about; and they went by the way \add leading\add* to the wilderness. 
\v 8 But the host of the Chaldeans pursued after the king, and overtook him in the \add country\add* beyond Jericho; and all his servants were dispersed from \add about\add* him. 
\v 9 They took the king, and brought him to the king of Babylon to Deblatha, and he judged him. 
\v 10 The king of Babylon killed the sons of Zedekiah before his eyes; and he killed all the princes of Judah in Deblatha. 
\v 11 He put out the eyes of Zedekiah, and bound him in fetters; and the king of Babylon brought him to Babylon, and put him into the grinding-house, until the day when he died. 
\p
\v 12 In the fifth month, on the tenth day of the month, Nabuzardan the captain of the guard, who waited on the king of Babylon, came to Jerusalem; 
\v 13 and he burnt the house of the Lord, and the king's house; and all the houses of the city, and every great house he burnt with fire. 
\v 14 The host of the Chaldeans that was with the captain of the guard pulled down all the wall of Jerusalem round about. 
\v 16 But the captain of the guard left the remnant of the people to be vinedressers and farmers. 
\p
\v 17 The Chaldeans broke in pieces the bronze pillars that were in the house of the Lord, and the bases, and the bronze sea that was in the house of the Lord, and they took the brass of it, and carried it away to Babylon. 
\v 18 Also the rim, and the bowls, and the flesh-hooks, and all the bronze vessels, with which they ministered; 
\v 19 and the basons, and the snuffers, and the oil-funnels, and the candlesticks, and the censers, and the cups, the golden, of gold, and the silver, of silver, the captain of the guard took away. 
\v 20 The two pillars, and the one sea, and the twelve bronze oxen under the sea, which \add things\add* king Solomon made for the house of the Lord; the brass of which \add articles\add* was without weight. 
\p
\v 21 As for the pillars, the height of one pillar was thirty-five cubits; and a line of twelve cubits compassed it round; and the thickness of it \add all\add* round was four fingers. 
\v 22 And \add there was\add* a bronze chapiter upon them, and the length was five cubits, \add even\add* the height of one chapiter; and \add there were\add* on the chapiter round about network and pomegranates, all of brass: and correspondingly the second pillar \add had\add* eight pomegranates to a cubit for the twelve cubits. 
\v 23 The pomegranates were ninety-six on a side; and all the pomegranates on the network round about were a hundred. 
\p
\v 24 The captain of the guard took the chief priest, and the second priest, and those who kept the way; 
\v 25 and one eunuch, who was over the men of war, and seven men of renown, who were in the king's presence, who were found in the city; and the scribe of the forces, who did the part of a scribe to the people of the land; and sixty men of the people of the land, who were found among the city. 
\v 26 Nabuzardan the captain of the king's guard took them, and brought them to the king of Babylon to Deblatha. 
\v 27 The king of Babylon struck them in Deblatha, in the land of Hamath. 
\p
\v 31 It happened in the thirty-seventh year after that Joakim king of Judah had been carried away captive, in the twelfth month, on the twenty-fourth \add day\add* of the month, \add that\add* Ulæmadachar king of Babylon, in the year in which he began to reign, raised the head of Joakim king of Judah, and shaved him, and brought him out of the house where he was kept, 
\v 32 and spoke kindly to him, and set his throne above the kings who were with him in Babylon, 
\v 33 and changed his prison garments: and he ate bread continually before him all the days that he lived. 
\v 34 His appointed portion was given him continually by the king of Babylon from day to day, until the day when he died. 
